<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Trade Surplus on Course for Post-Reunification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Germany's trade surplus rose
sharply to 13.4 billion marks (7.34 billion U.S. dollars) in June
from 9.8 billion marks (5.4 billion dollars) in May and just 6.5
billion (3.6 billion dollars) in June 1996, the federal statistics
office announced today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Wiesbaden-based office, Germany's exports
surged 23.3 percent in June in year-on-year terms and imports were
up 13.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
For the first half of 1997 as a whole, German exports totaled
424 billion marks (232 billion dollars) and imports 366 billion
marks (200 billion dollars), adding up to a surplus of 58 billion
marks (32 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Officials said they were expecting the trade surplus to top 100
billion marks (55 billion dollars) by the end of 1997, the highest
since German reunification in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the massive expansion in visible trade surplus,
Germany's current account balance, which includes trade in
services, also swung into a surplus of 4.0 billion marks (2.2
billion dollars) in June, compared with the deficits of 2.6
billion marks (1.4 billion dollars) in May and 0.8 billion marks
(438 million dollars) in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
Although the current account for the first half year was still
in deficit, the gap was reduced to just 4.8 billion marks (2.6
billion dollars) compared with 6.3 billion marks (3.5 billion
dollars) a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
