<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Pledges Further Support to Dhaka's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Mitsuo Sato, president of the
Asian Development Bank (ADB), today said that his bank will
continue to remain a strong and committed development partner of
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here today, he disclosed that
"in recent years, the bank has committed, on an average, about 270
million U.S. dollars every year in loans to Bangladesh. In 1997,
the bank's lending could rise to about 420 million dollars for
five projects."
</P>
<P>
The ADB president, who came here on Saturday for a three-day
visit, spoke highly of Dhaka's efforts in poverty alleviation and
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
He said the Bangladeshi government was pursing a policy
conducive to economic development and expressed the hope that
Bangladesh would be in a "better position to play a more active
role in a global economic system."
</P>
<P>
The ADB is an important donor of this underdeveloped South
Asian country and since the beginning of the bank's operation in
1973, it has extended 123 loans totaling 5 billion dollars
primarily from the bank's soft loan window -- the Asian
Development Fund.
</P>
<P>
However, due to the sharp fall of the availability of soft
funds for development purposes, the ADB has reduced the amount of
soft loan to its member countries in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"In view of Bangladesh's needs, the bank will attempt to
explore new co-financing possibilities for high priority projects,
particularly for infrastructure development," said Sato.
</P>
<P>
As for the plan to construct a barrage over the Ganges river,
Sato said that his bank will field a technical team to conduct a
study in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The Ganges barrage is estimated to cost about 6 billion
dollars,
"given the size of the project, both the feasibility study and
project implementation will need to be undertaken by a consortium
of donors," Sato added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, the ADB chief also called on Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina, who said her government had been trying to quicken
the process of development and assistance from development
partners like the ADB would help accelerate the process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
