<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: A Visit Aimed at Building 21st Century-Oriented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng's
visit to Malaysia and Singapore from August 21 to 26 has laid a
solid foundation for building a 21st century-oriented relationship
of good neighborliness and mutual trust with the countries in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
China's ties with the two countries date back to ancient
times. Recent years witnessed a strong surge in their political,
economic, trade, educational and technological cooperation. In
particular, frequent visits by their leaders greatly boosted their
mutual trust and bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Li's talks with leaders of the two countries covered both
bilateral ties and regional and international issues, but the
focus was on how to build a relationship of good neighborliness
and friendly cooperation for the next century.
</P>
<P>
In Malaysia, both Li and his Malaysian counterpart, Mahathir
Mohamad, held that despite major changes in the world since the
establishment of diplomatic ties, the two countries have been able
to treat their bilateral relations in the long-term and strategic
perspectives. The deepening mutual trust between their leaders
further injected a new life into bilateral cooperation which has
been gaining momentum over the years.
</P>
<P>
China and Malaysia have been working closely together on many
issues in international arena. Mahathir has on many occasions
refuted the "China threat" theory and voiced his support for
China's stand on the issue of human rights. His advocacy for a
re-examination of the 50-year-old Universal Declaration of Human
Rights also won China's appreciation and support.
</P>
<P>
The two premiers also noted that the time when a few powers
dominated the world was long gone and the current trend toward a
multi-polar world is conducive to peace and stability both in Asia
and the rest of the world. As a result, all countries and forces
in the world should strengthen consultation and coordination in
the fight against hegemonism.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, whose economic and trade ties with China have
grown in strength, Li's talks with Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong
centered on how to expand the scope of bilateral cooperation by
tapping each other's potential.
</P>
<P>
Li told his host that China's long-term development strategy
has created broad prospects for Singaporean businessmen to play a
more active role in its economic construction.
</P>
<P>
As his visit coincided with the 30th anniversary of the
founding of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, Premier Li
also took this opportunity to reaffirm China's policy on
developing good neighborly and friendly ties with the regional
grouping.
</P>
<P>
He unveiled a "five-point" principle governing China's future
relations with ASEAN, which includes mutual respect, closer
dialogue and consultation, mutual benefit and joint development,
and seeking common ground while reserving differences.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of South China Sea which was left over by history,
Li reiterated China's principle of putting the dispute aside to
give way to joint exploration. He said that the issue should be
properly solved by peaceful means and through friendly
consultation in accordance with relevant international laws and
marine laws.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li also made a major statement on economic and trade
relations with ASEAN. By taking advantage of their supremacy, he
said, China and the ASEAN countries can cooperate more effectively
in the future, especially in the financial field.
</P>
<P>
All these statements demonstrate that China highly values the
positive role played by ASEAN in the Asia-Pacific region and hopes
to further develop ties with the regional grouping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
