<HEADLINE> UK Police to Launch Drug Law Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Police Foundation, an
independent research charity, is launching a two-year inquiry into
the UK's drugs laws, and it will review the workings of the 1971
Misuse of Drugs Act.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports today said the study, funded by a number of
charities, will be carried out by a 12-member panel including
lawyers, academics and police officers.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry will consider whether policies pursued by
successive governments have worked. It is also expected to focus
on whether the 1971 Misuse of Drugs Act needs to be changed in the
light of the scale of illegal drug use today.
</P>
<P>
It will examine the possibilities of tougher enforcement,
decriminalization, legalization and greater use of some drugs for
medicinal purposes across the range of substances covered by the
act.
</P>
<P>
The foundation said an independent and objective review in an
area where there is little consensus was overdue, and the inquiry
was set up partly because of the failure of politicians to address
drug use in Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
