<HEADLINE> Dublin Considering to Set Up Commission on Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government is
considering to establish a statutory commission with High Court
powers of investigation and prosecution to monitor various cash
payments to politicians.
</P>
<P>
The Dublin government would make it a crime for bankers,
accountants, and professional advisers not to disclose or unusual
financial transactions involving politicians or public servants to
the new commission, according to a report in today's Irish Times
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties may accept the proposed measures as
limited safeguards but they would insist that a new tribunal is
urgently required to investigate other controversial business and
financial decisions involving former Prime Minister Charles
Haughey, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Haughey, a three-time prime minister, is expected to be
severely censured by the new tribunal because of his consistent
denials that he had received 1.3 million Irish pounds (about 1.9
million U.S. dollars) from an Irish businessman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
