<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Dismisses Turkish Community's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government today
dismissed the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash's war threats
and expressed the hope that the peace process will continue
despite the deadlock in the direct talks between the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides.
</P>
<P>
At his daily press briefing here, Government Spokesman Manolis
Christofides said if Turkey, which supports the Turkish
Cypriot-controlled northern Cyprus politically and militarily,
declares war against Cyprus, this will also mean declaration of
war against Greece, a close ally of the Greek Cypriot-ruled Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on statements made by Denktash on Monday, who
warned that if the Greek Cypriot side joins the European Union
(EU) using the name "Cyprus", the Turkish Cypriots will "justly
object" as they will not benefit from the EU accession. This will
spark a new war on the island, said Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Denktash also reiterated that he will not return to the
negotiating table unless the EU accession plans are frozen.
</P>
<P>
This eastern Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkish troops invaded and took over the 37 per cent of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece, one of the three guarantor powers of Cyprus'
independence under the 1960 treaty of establishment of the Cyprus
Republic, has warned Turkey that any further advance of the
Turkish troops toward the government-controlled southern part of
the island will mean war between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Christofides also said that if Denktash's threats of war are
directed toward the EU, then this is "a clearly quixotic
attitude."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated the wish of the Greek Cypriot side
for peace, saying that the two communities should jointly build a
"common home" and for the happiness and prosperity of all Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that this is a crucial period for the Cyprus
problem. "Even though the first and second round of direct talks
between President (Glafcos) Clerides and Denktash have not been
successful, the process will continue," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We are waiting for the next step which is expected to be very
serious," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash held two rounds of U.N.-sponsored direct
talks, in July and August, which came to a deadlock due to
Denktash's insistence on the EU accession issue.
</P>
<P>
The EU reaffirmed on July 15 its decision that accession
negotiations with Cyprus will begin early next year. Cyprus
applied for full EU membership in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
