<HEADLINE> Roundup: De Klerk's Departure From Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Yegang &AMP; Zhao Yi)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- South African opposition
National Party leader and former South African president F.W. De
Klerk announced today that he will retire after engaging in 25 years
of political activities.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in Cape Town, De Klerk said he is the last
high-profile link with National Party's past and that by quitting
active politics, he hopes to boost the party's image as a new and
reformed political force in the country.
</P>
<P>
Announcing his retirement from active politics, De Klerk
reiterated that there is a urgent need for political realignment
in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"With my retirement, I wish to open a door for the National
Party to provide further proof of its dynamic break with the
past, with a view to best enabling it to play its full role in
the realignment process," he said.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk said he will remain committed to everything which
the new National Party stands for and will continue to promote
these goals after his retirement, both inside the country and
overseas.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the National Party has, at his instigation,
decided to move away from centralism and to allow for greater
autonomy of the party's regional structures.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk's sudden announcement about his departure from
politics has surprised many political organizations in South
Africa, and resulted in different comments, but mainly praises.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela said De Klerk's
contribution to leading South Africa from its painful past to its
present political dispensation should be recognized.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever mistakes he may have made, and it is possible that
he has made very fundamental mistakes as many of us have done, I
hope South Africa will not forget the role he has played,"
Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and De Klerk shared the Nobel Peace Prize in 1993 for
their contribution to bringing about peaceful change in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Party leader Tony Leon pointed out that De Klerk
would and should be remembered for the February 2, 1990 speech,
in which he announced Nelson Mandela's release form jail and the
unbanning of political organizations.
</P>
<P>
"While there might be other criticisms of De Klerk's
leadership, history and South Africa owed him a debt of gratitude
for this," Leon said.
</P>
<P>
Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, Chairman of the ruling African
National Congress Women Alliance, described De Klerk's
resignation as the " second courageous concession".
</P>
<P>
Just as De Klerk had taken the right decision when he conceded
apartheid had failed, so too was his resignation a concession
that the National Party could no longer make a positive
contribution to non-racial democracy, she said.
</P>
<P>
New Process Movement leader Roelf Meyer said: "Together with
the whole of South Africa, we want to thank him today for the
courage and vision that he displayed in 1990, which helped to
lift our country from rut of the past and put it on the road
towards democratization."
</P>
<P>
The Freedom Front's General Constand Viljoen welcomed De
Klerks's decision to quit his position as a "very positive
development for Afrikaner politics".
</P>
<P>
De Klerks's departure opened up the possibility of greater
solidarity of approach in the areas of self-determination and the
future of the Afrikaner, Viljoen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
