<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel Indicates Willingness to Resume Contacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 26 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel said today that Germany and other European Union (EU)
countries would resume contacts with Iran soon, possibly on the
occasion of the UN General Assembly meetings in New York by the
end of September.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel made the remarks after new Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Charrasi on Monday voiced readiness for a meeting with
Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
"If Mr Kinkel was interested in such a meeting, I would welcome
it," said Charrasi in an interview with the German news agency DPA
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We are also ready to resume dialogue with the EU, but so far
we have not yet received any official offer," he added.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German newspaper Neue Ruhr Zeitung,
Kinkel said he was in favor of resuming contact with the
apparently more liberal new government in Teheran.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the UN General Assembly meetings in New York
next month would be an appropriate occasion for an initial
encounter between Charrasi and foreign ministers from Luxemburg,
the Netherlands and Britain. But he stopped short of saying
whether he himself was planning to meet his Iranian counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Germany and other EU nations withdrew their ambassadors from
Iran in April after a German court linked Iranian leadership to
the killings of four Kurdish dissidents in a Berlin restaurant in
1992.
</P>
<P>
There have been renewed hopes among EU countries for improved
ties with Teheran after Iran's new president, Mohammad Khatami,
took office on August 3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
