<HEADLINE> Hamas Rejects to Suspend Arm Attacks Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas) today rejected the Palestinian National
Authority's (PNA) request to suspend arm attacks on Israel,
reported the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Hamas said in a statement this afternoon that although the
PNA officials have called for a hold to the violent activities
against Israel, it viewed the arm struggle as a strategic choice
and a strong line of defense for the Palestinian people and
refused to stop it.
</P>
<P>
A senior Palestinian official confirmed that in conciliatory
talks Monday, the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) asked
the Islamic militants opposed to the Oslo peace accords to stop
violent attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
"We have asked the opposition groups to oppose peace deals
only through democratic and peaceful means and not through
military attacks," Tayeb Abdel Rahim, a senior aide to PNA
President Yasser Arafat, said after a national unity meeting
with Muslim militants in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise the (Palestinian National) Authority will by law
crack down on those who try to embarrass it by taking the law
into their own hands," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Rahim said that Hamas has demanded the release of its
activists from PLO jails, but the PNA refused until Hamas
agrees to respect Arafat's peace commitments to Israel.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the unity talks were aimed at finding common
ground between the PNA and its opponents in light of "Israel's
refusal to implement peace deals."
</P>
<P>
He said that no agreements had yet been reached and that the
talks would continue. 
</P>
