<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium to Destroy Last Batch of Anti-Personnel Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Belgium is to become a country
free of anti-personnel mines after it destroys its last batch of
such military devices.
</P>
<P>
A train load of more than 115,000 anti-personnel mines is
scheduled to leave Bertrix late today and head for neighboring
Germany, where the mines will be destroyed through incineration.
</P>
<P>
Belgium is not capable of destroying the mines via incineration
simply because of technical reasons, according to the local
television RTBF.
</P>
<P>
Belgium is the first country in the world to have made it a law
in 1995 banning the production, exportation and utilization of
anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
Now all European Union member states, except for Greece and
Finland, have also decided to ban anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that upwards of 100 million
anti-personnel mines have so far been laid out throughout the
world and they combine to claim an annual casualties of 20,000
people, mostly innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
Most of the live anti-personnel mines can be found in former
conflict regions such as Cambodia, Bosnia-Herzegovina and Somalia
and along former Cold-War foes like Finland and Russia.
</P>
<P>
RTBF television described anti-personnel mines as the "weapons
of the cowards." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
