<HEADLINE> 6 Palestinians Injured in Clash With Israelis in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Six Palestinian demonstrators,
including a policeman, were injured as Israeli soldiers fired
rubber bullets and tear gas today to disperse the protesters in
the west Bank city of Bethlehem in the second day of clashes.
</P>
<P>
The clash took place near the Jewish holy site of Rachel'
Tomb. To protest the ongoing closure imposed by Israel, three
dozens of Palestinian youths threw stones at the soldiers guarding
the site, who retaliated with rubber bullets and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
About 10 Palestinian school children were sent to hospital for
treatment for gas inhalation after some of the gas grenades fired
by Israeli soldiers fell into their school yard, according to the
Jerusalem-based Palestinian news service the Jerusalem Media and
Communications Center.
</P>
<P>
This is the second day of clashes in Bethlehem, which is the
only West Bank city that is still under an internal travel ban
imposed by Israel. Three Palestinian protesters were wounded by
rubber bullets fired by Israeli soldiers during Monday's clash at
the same site.
</P>
<P>
Israel has recently lifted the internal travel ban on all
other Palestinian cities in the West Bank in a gesture to ease the
sanctions imposed following the July 30 suicide bombing attack in
Jewish west Jerusalem, which killed 16 people and injured 170
others.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Israeli militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas)
claimed responsibility for the attack. The reason that Israel
maintains the internal travel ban on Bethlehem is that it regards
the people who masterminded the Mahane Yehuda bombings might be
hiding in the city. Not long ago, Palestinian police uncovered a
Hamas bomb factory near Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rising tension between the two sides due to
Israel's continued sanctions against the Palestinians, Israeli
Army Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin Shahak downplayed the prospect
of an immediate explosion in the territories.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and
Defense Committee, Shahak noted that tension had existed in the
territories for a long time, and he did not expect the situation
to explode in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
He said the reason was that everyone is now waiting for the
first visit to the region by United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who is due here in the second week of
September.
</P>
<P>
However, the army chief warned that there was an accumulation
of anger and pressure in the territories, and the tension could
trigger Palestinian violence at any time.
</P>
<P>
Israeli opposition Meretz Party's head Yossi Sarid attacked the
government for maintaining the sanctions against the
Palestinians, including the total closure, barring Palestinian
workers from entering Israel and freezing most of the tax
revenues owed to the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
Sarid said that if a Palestinian father of 10 children
continued to be barred from working in Israel, then he could not
feed his family. He called for an immediate end to the sanctions
in order to revive the peace process that has been stalemated
since March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
