<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Welcomes Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng
reiterated here today that China will continue to attract foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions from Singaporean businessmen before
wrapping up his three-day visit here, Li said that attracting
foreign investment is a long-term policy of China and constitutes
an important part of its reform and opening policy,
</P>
<P>
Although foreign investment dropped somewhat in the first six
months of this year to 23.3 billion U.S. dollars compared with the
same period last year, Li said, the fluctuation is quite normal
and more investment is geared toward infrastructure and high-tech
industries.
</P>
<P>
He said, "China will continue to give tax exemption to hi-tech
projects or those with strong competitive edge in international
market."
</P>
<P>
In a question-and-answer session following a speech before
Singaporean businessmen, Li also talked about China's
determination to invigorate state-owned enterprises in its drive
to build a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that to invigorate state-run enterprises, a mechanism
is needed to merge them or declare them bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
But he emphasized that the government must be very careful in
implementing the bankruptcy law because excessive bankruptcies may
cause high unemployment or social instability.
</P>
<P>
Li also told them that foreigners are also welcome to invest in
China's village and township enterprises, some of which are very
large and well-equipped. 
</P>
