<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Health Service Waiting Lists Getting Longer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The National Health Service
waiting lists are soaring because the axing of tax relief has
driven people away from private health care, it was claimed here
today.
</P>
<P>
Private health insurance firms said 100,000 people have
canceled policies since the Budget released early July and up to
half a million are set to join the exodus.
</P>
<P>
Abolishing tax relief on private health insurance was a Labor
manifesto pledge designed to fund cuts in VAT on fuel.
</P>
<P>
The tax relief, claimed by 600,000 pensioners before the
Budget, cut the cost of private insurance by about a third --
worth around 40 pounds (64 US dollars) a month.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the cancelation would create a cash crisis
for the NHS and inevitably lead to longer waiting lists and poorer
services.
</P>
<P>
However, the British Medical Association and Department of
Health insisted that if the number of private patients slumped, a
corresponding number of doctors would return to the State sector.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the Department of Health said, "We are
hopeful any extra burden of patients using the NHS would be
catered for by doctors who find they have less private work."
</P>
<P>
Evan Harris, the Liberal Democrats' NHS spokesman, said that
Labor's policies have left the NHS 1 billion pounds (1.6 billion
US dollars) worse off than it should have been since the election.
</P>
<P>
According to figures gathered by Harris, who was former member
of the British Medical Association Council, the NHS has seen
real-terms cuts of at least half a billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
Another half billion raised through tax changes should have
been channeled back into hospitals and doctors' surgeries but was
used for other things, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
Harris also said he had evidence that hospitals were being
forced to give priority to non-urgent operations such as breast
reductions while patients needing cataract surgery or hip
replacements were forced to wait.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the number of emergency admissions has already
risen ten-fold from 4,000 to 45,000 in the 14 months up to June
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
