<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Set to Tighten Sanctions on Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA (Nigeria), August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS) is set to tighten its sanctions
on the military government of Sierra Leone, a top Nigerian
officer said here today.
</P>
<P>
A. Abubakar, Nigeria's Chief of Staff, made the revelation at
the 16th meeting of the chiefs of staff from the ECOWAS member
states, held this morning at the ECOWAS Secretariat in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
"From all indications, peaceful resolutions through dialogue
have failed," in Sirrra leone, Abubakar said, referring to the
announcement made by Major Johnny Kromah that his government will
stay in power until 2001.
</P>
<P>
Kromah came into power on May 25 through a military coup in
which Sierra Leone's legitimate president Tejan Kabbah was
ousted.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS has been making efforts to reinstate Kabbah as
presidency in the past two months, but it has not made any
progress.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said,"The next option without recourse to the use of
offensive action, is the enforcement of sanctions/embargo on the
regime, through economic blocade."
</P>
<P>
He warned that Kromah's refusal to reinstall ousted president
Tejan Kabbah is meant to destabilize the peace and harmony in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the violent overthrow of Kabbah is "
capable of reversing the gains we have made in Liberia".
</P>
<P>
"If there is no peace in Sierra Leone, it will certainly be
difficult, if not possible, to fully establish stability and
normalcy in Liberia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting of the chiefs of staff is expected to make its
recommendations to the ECOWAS summit scheduled for Thursday in
Lagos, Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
However, observers doubted if ECOWAS's sanctions will
work.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS chiefs of staff were also expected to discuss a
framework on the restructuring and training of the armed forces
as well as the police and security agencies of Liberia by ECOWAS
peace-keeping forces in that country known as ECOMOG. 
</P>
