<HEADLINE> WFP Begins Emergency Airlift of Seeds to DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) today began airlifting urgently-needed seeds to to
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to enable returned
refugees to plant in time.
</P>
<P>
A news release issued here today said that a WFP chartered
C-130 aircraft landed this morning in Bukavu in the southern Kivu
area with 18 tons of seeds.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of 280 tons of maize seed, bean seed and soya
seed will be delivered in 16 flights over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The release noted that the WFP is providing a one-month food
package to some 15,000 families receiving the seeds as part of a
"seed protection" program to discourage hungry families from
eating their seeds.
</P>
<P>
Aid agencies operating in the area are supplying food and
seeds to tens of thousands of families who have recently returned
to their homes around Bukavu as they are unable to sow crops for
the next harvest due to arrive in January 1998, said the release.
</P>
<P>
The WFP has been providing airlift support for the Great Lakes
emergency since October 1996 with WFP aircraft ferrying a total
of 8,346 tons of food into the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. organization has also participated in a massive
airlift refugee repatriation operation which began at the end of
April 1997 and to date it has flown some 50,000 refugees back to
Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
