<HEADLINE> French Finance Minister: Euro Must Start on Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 26 (Xinhua) -- French Finance Minister Dominique
Strauss-Kahn today warned that a delay in starting the single
European currency, the Euro, would mean the end of the project.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Germany's Deutschlandfunk radio today,
Strauss-Kahn said, "It must come on January 1, 1999. A delay would
be the end of the Euro."
</P>
<P>
Any delay was neither legally possible nor desirable, he added.
</P>
<P>
The French finance minister also stressed that France would
adhere to the conditions set by the EU for qualifying for the
single currency, including the one which requires a member state's
budget deficit to be less than 3 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
France, whose current budget deficit stood at about 3.5 to 3.7
percent of GDP, would bring itself "quite close" to the 3-percent
target thanks to measures introduced by the government in July,
Strauss-Kahn said. 
