<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Expected to Produce Less Wheat in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Canada's wheat production is
expected to be the lowest in nine years, Statistics Canada
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Total wheat production has been adversely affected by 2.5
million fewer seeded acres this year and a reported yield decrease
of six bushels per acre," the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
"Wheat production is expected to drop by 6.8 million tons this
year, the largest drop since 1988 when production fell by 10
million tons," the agency said in its July 31 estimate.
</P>
<P>
Extremely dry conditions throughout July have taken their toll
on all crops in Canada's major producing provinces of Western
Canada, and farmers there are expecting much lower yields than
last year for all major crops.
</P>
<P>
Barley production is expected to fall by 2.0 million tons
compared with last year because of 0.5 million fewer seeded acres
and an expected reduced yield of six bushels per acre.
</P>
<P>
Of the major crops surveyed, only canola and flaxseed were
reported to show an increase in production.
</P>
<P>
Canola acreage rose by 3.4 million acres this year, but the
expected drop in yield of four bushels per acre will moderate the
rise in production to 1 million tons. 
</P>
