<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman International Bank has launched a public
issue of its equity shares aimed at increasing its capital as part
of efforts to strengthen its lending capacity, the Omani news
agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The issue of 6,074,602 shares, which is open exclusively for
Omani nationals and 100 Omani companies, is priced at 1.3
U.S. dollars per share. The issue will close for subscription on
September 21.
</P>
<P>
After the issue, the share capital of the bank will stand at
17.7 million dollars, making it the best capitalized Omani bank,
the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The increase in capital will considerably enhance the bank's
lending capacity, it added.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian industry utilized no more than 53 percent of
its overall production capacity, semi-official Jordan Times
today quoted a study by the Royal Scientific Society (RSS) as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The figure comes from the fact that the medium and small size
industries are now comparatively active while the large-size ones,
except the mining ones, are in a sluggish condition, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the low utilization rate to limited resource of
funds.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government earlier admitted that its economy was
in recess and is currently undergoing a restructure prescribed by
the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A Jordanian delegation led by Minister of Trade,
Industry and Supply Hani Moulki left here today for Damascus to
attend the annual Damascus International Fair scheduled for
Thursday, Jordan's official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's participation stemmed from its keenness to enhance
trade and economic ties with Syria, said delegation member Haidar
Murad, chairman of the Federation of Jordanian Chambers of
Commerce, in a statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 Jordanian industrial businesses will take part in
the fair, displaying samples of their products and introducing
their investment services.
</P>
<P>
The balance of trade between the two countries is now in favor
of Syria, which sold Jordan 99 million Jordanian dinars (about 140
million U.S. dollars) worth of goods in 1996. Jordan exported 41
million dinars (about 58 million dollars) worth of goods to Syria
in the same year.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Despite strong opposition from local producers, Jordan
has decided to open its mineral water market to foreign
competitors in a bid to secure its entry to the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The Jordan Times newspaper reported today the Jordanian
government would allow for the import of mineral water from Arab
and other foreign countries from the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Hani Moulki, minister of trade, industry and supply, was quoted
as saying the measure is aimed at pushing Jordanian companies to
improve mineral water production and their competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Moulki made the remarks Monday while meeting with members of
the Amman Chamber of Industry (ACI), who object to the government
decision, claiming it will inflict heavy losses on the domestic
industry.
</P>
<P>
Costs of mineral water production in neighboring Arab countries
were far less than in Jordan, said an ACI spokesman who declined
to give his name. Therefore, Jordan's products would be vulnerable
in price competition.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jordanian government decided to raise water
price by 150 percent, due to severe shortage of water resources,
which ACI said would further increase the costs of local mineral
water production like "spreading oil over troubled water."
</P>
<P>
Jordan has five mineral water factories, which have a total
capital of 4 million Jordanian dinars (about 5.6 million
U.S. dollars) and offer job opportunities to 1,500 people. There
is no official figure as to their annual profits.
</P>
<P>
Mineral water imports have been rare for years in the kingdom,
which is now making intensive efforts for WTO membership through
improving its market access to foreign goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
