<HEADLINE> Baghdad Awaits Iran's Good-Will Gestures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said today that it was
waiting to see the new Iranian government to prove its good
intentions towards the Arab world including Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"It is crucial that the new Iranian administration demonstrate
its good will not only towards Iraq but also towards all Arab
countries," said Nabil Negm, Iraq's chief delegate to the
Cairo-based Arab League (AL).
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Middle East News Agency quoted Negm as saying following
his meeting with Zakaria Azmi, AL assistant secretary general for
political affairs, that Iraq had displayed "genuine desire for
neighborly relations" with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"The ball is now in the Iranian court, and Tehran has to prove
its well intentions towards the Arabs and stop interfering in
their internal affairs," he added.
</P>
<P>
Negm said that to improve ties, Tehran should free the 20,000
Iraqi prisoners of war captured during the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq war
and return Iraqi aircraft sent to Iran in 1991 to escape attacks
by allied forces during the Gulf War over Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein decided on August 18 to allow
from September 4 Iranian visits to Shiite Muslim shrines in Iraq,
which were banned since the two countries went to war in
1980. Nearly one million people were killed in the eight-year war.
</P>
<P>
On August 17, newly-elected Iranian President Mohammed Khatami
appealed to Baghdad to show "good-will" and release Iranian
prisoners of war he said Iraq was still holding.
</P>
<P>
A senior Iranian Foreign Ministry official on August 18 called
for the two countries to conclude a "peace accord" to settle all
the outstanding problems between them.
</P>
<P>
Nine years after the UN-brokered cease fire of August 18, 1988,
Iran and Iraq have never formally made peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
