<HEADLINE> European Shares Down on Weak Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe all
extended Monday's losses and ended down sharply, with Frankfurt
worst hit, undermined by the dollar's drop and worries about rise
in German interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The London market, which was closed Monday for a bank holiday,
ended lower but off weakest levels of the session. Dealers said
that futures and a weak performance on Wall Street added to the
negative sentiment, keeping the FTSE 100 index subdued below the
4,900-level.
</P>
<P>
Trading remained thin after the long weekend, and banking
stocks were down. The index ended down 14.8 points at 4,886.3.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt plunged by 2.8 percent after the
dollar tumbled below 1.80 marks and prospects for a near-term
German interest rate hike weighed on market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index was dragged below the key level of 4,000
points and was 112.46 points lower at 3,959.33 by the close of the
session.
</P>
<P>
Stocks on the Paris bourse were also lower as bonds turned
weaker. The CAC-40 index finished at 2,869, down 29.31 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
