<HEADLINE> Japan the Big Winner in Universiade Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MESSINA, Sicily, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Japan was the biggest winner
on the opening day of the Universiade swimming tournament by taking
three out of six golds on offer here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The American swimmers won two titles while the remaining gold was
taken by Hungarian.
</P>
<P>
Junko Onishi gave Japan the first swimming gold as she beat all her
opponents to take the women's 100 meters butterfly title with a time
of 1:00.40.
</P>
<P>
Fumie Kurotori followed suite with a victory in the women's 400
meters individual medley. Her winning time was 4:46.20.
</P>
<P>
The silver medal of the event went to Hana Cerna of Czech Republic
while Elli Overton of Australia finished with a bronze.
</P>
<P>
Japan's third swimming gold of the day came from Chikara Nakashita
who snatched the title of the men's 200 meters breaststroke with a
time of 2:16.35.
</P>
<P>
Two American swimmers Scott Werner and William Shefchik finished
second and third at 2:17.41 and 2:17.50 respectively.
</P>
<P>
But it was the Americans who took the first gold of the Universiade
swimming tournament. Suzanne L. Black swam 8:45.82 to win the women's
800 meters freestyle title, beating her fellow American Joy E. Stover
to the second place at 8:47.73.
</P>
<P>
Eri Yamanoi of Japan won the bronze medal of the event at 8:48.65.
</P>
<P>
The title of the women's 4X200 meters freestyle relay was also won
by the Americans.
</P>
<P>
The American quartet enjoyed a great advantage in the race and beat
the eventual runners-up Australia by more than 14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The Americans' winning time was 8:12.16, the Australia came second
at 8:26.97 and the Italians finished third at 8;27.11.
</P>
<P>
The men's 200 meters freestyle gold was taken by Bela Szabados of
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Szabados swam the fastest time of 1:50.70, beating runner-up Scott
D. Goldblatt of the United States by 1.43 seconds. Michael Kiedel of
Germany took away the bronze medal with a time of 1:52.13.
</P>
<P>
The Universiade swimming tournament continues on Wednesday with six
gold medals at stake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
