<HEADLINE> Turkish President's Cairo Visit Aims to Appease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel's visit to Cairo scheduled on September 16 aims to allay
Arab apprehension about Ankara's growing military ties with
Israel, the Turkish ambassador to Egypt said today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and his
Turkish counterpart comes within the context of continued
consultation between the countries' leaderships, Yacar Yakis told
the Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Yakis said that Demirel's one-day visit to Egypt will cover the
latest developments in the region and bilateral and regional
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"President Demirel's visit is aimed at dispelling fears of
Turkey's likely distancing itself from the Arab world and getting
closer to Israel," Yakis said, adding that relations between
Turkey and Israel are not of any dimensions causing anxiety.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed a military cooperation accord in
February 1996 and announced in May that they will stage joint
naval exercises in the eastern Mediterranean in this summer.
</P>
<P>
The planned maneuvers provoked outcries from Arab countries,
especially Syria, which sees itself as the target of the
Turkish-Israeli alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Turkish summit, which was originally set for May,
was postponed in the wake of the planned naval war games.
</P>
<P>
There have been various reports on the possible postponement of
the maneuvers in view of the strong Arab protests, while Turkish
defense and foreign officials give contradictory replies and
answers to it.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here said earlier that the Egyptian-Turkish
summit will focus on means to enhance relations between the two
countries and increase the volume of trade, the situation in
northern Iraq, as well as the Mideast peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
