<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laws Urged for Beira Corridor in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Transport and Energy
Minister Enos Chikowore today called for the establishment of the
Beira Development Corridor (BDC) through an appropriate legal
instrument.
</P>
<P>
Addressing participants to a Joint Technical Unit (JTU)
meeting on BDC, Chikowore said the instrument would go a long way
in facilitating the integration of the economies affected by the
BDC through the promotion of common policies and practices.
</P>
<P>
The current Beira corridor is a railway and road network
running between Zimbabwe's eastern border town of Mutare and
Mozambican port city of Beira.
</P>
<P>
The BDC concept was consistent with the thrust of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) and Southern African
Transport and Communication Commission (SATCC) of promoting
integrated, harmonized, efficient and cost effective transport
and telecommunication systems within the region, Chikowore noted.
</P>
<P>
The JTU was formed at the eighth annual meeting of ministers
of foreign affairs of Zimbabwe and Mozambique held in Mozambique
in August last year where the two countries agreed to deepen and
widen cooperation in the development of the Beira corridor which
provide the shortest outlet for Zimbabwe's export.
</P>
<P>
The ministers of transport set up a joint working group
consisting of technical experts and business representatives from
both countries with a mandate to advise on how the BDC could be
created, organized and promoted.
</P>
<P>
The joint working group was later expanded to include Malawi
and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"The benefits of establishing the BDC are clearly immense,"
Chikowore stressed, adding, "an appropriate legal instrument will
set out the principles and parameters to guide the various actors
involved in the transformation of the corridor." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
