<HEADLINE> Iraq's Kurdish Group Denies Support of Outlawed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK), one of the main warring parties in northern
Iraq, today denied reports that the group supports the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
The PUK office in Ankara said in a statement that press
reports regarding this are incorrect and baseless, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The PUK statement came amidst recent reports from various
press organizations that the PUK and the PKK are joining hands
in the fighting against the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP),
the main rival of the PUK in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The KDP led by Massoud Barzani accused the PUK of cooperating
with the PKK rebels stationed in the region last weekend, saying
that their cooperation has reached an alarming level.
</P>
<P>
The PUK statement said that the PUK led by Jalal Talabani
still abides by the cease-fire agreement in spite of "a KDP
provocation."
</P>
<P>
Noting that the clashes between the PKK and PUK took place
far away from the ceas-fire line, the statement said that the KDP
uses this allegation as an excuse because it could not fulfill
its promise to Turkey that it will eradicate the PKK in the
region.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the PUK attached importance to the
invitation of Turkey, the United States and Britain to bring
it and the KDP to Washington for talks in a bid to revive the
sluggish Ankara peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Ankara peace process started after the three countries
convinced the KDP and PUK to end a bloody conflict in northern
Iraq late last year.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry has reportedly conveyed its complaint
to the PUK about the activities of the PKK in the PUK-controlled
areas, warning that this is unacceptable to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey launched a massive cross-border military campaign in
mid-May this year in a bid to wipe out the outlawed PKK rebels
there, triggering strong criticism from the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The northern part of Iraq has been controlled by the two
Kurdish groups since the Gulf War in 1991, but it split into
rival zones after the KDP and PUK began fighting each other in
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
