<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Traditional Healers Close to AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean traditional healers
today said they have reached advanced stages in their search for
a drug that could kill, destroy or weaken the HIV/AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of primary care physicians of Zimbabwe,
President of the Zimbabwe National Traditional Healers
Association Professor Gordon Chavunduka said a potential AIDS
drug had been identified and that isolated compounds were
undergoing tests.
</P>
<P>
''We have not yet found a cure for AIDS. But we have isolated
some compounds which are undergoing tests in a laboratory,'' he
said, adding, ''Thus, we have a potential AIDS drug in our
possession but more work still needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
He said if the attempts were successful, formal clinical
trials would be conducted.
</P>
<P>
He asked the government to avail as much funds for the
development of traditional medicines as was provided for the
improvement of the modern health sector. 
</P>
