<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's 35 Percent of Population Poor: World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Some 312 million people live
in poverty, or some 35 percent of India's total population, the
World Bank said in a report released here today.
</P>
<P>
However, the report, entitled "India: Achievements and
Challenges in Reducing Poverty," also said that if India's 6-7
percent growth rates of the last three years are sustained, and
income distribution remains at its present levels, poverty could
plummet from its current rate of 35 percent to 6.3 percent by
2005.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, in the early 1950s, nearly half of the
country's population was living in poverty. Since then, poverty
has declined, but at a slow rate than other Asian countries.
Today, roughly one-third of the population is poor by the same
standards as the early 1950s. However, due to rapid population
growth, even these modest rates of poverty reduction have not been
sufficient to reduce the numbers of poor people, which have risen
from about 164 million in 1951 to 312 million in 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank report said India is home to the largest
concentration of poor people of any single country in the world.
This is especially true in the rural areas, where nearly three out
of four Indians and 77 percent of Indian live poor.
</P>
<P>
Extending the definition of poverty to include other indicators
of well-being such as health and education, the report showed
India has made substantial gains in poverty reduction over the
past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, India has not yet achieved the
momentum needed to lift the great majority of its poor into the
economic mainstream. Infant mortality rates, as one example, fell
from 146 deaths per thousand births in the 1950s to 80 at the
start of the 1990s. Yet the rate is still one of the highest in
the world today. Life expectancy in India is 60 years and well
below that of China, 69 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Villagers Protest Use of Cyanide in Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Around 250 Turkish villagers
occupied the Bosporus Bridge linking Asia and Europe in Istanbul
for one and a half hours today to protest cyanide use in gold
processing.
</P>
<P>
The villagers, who traveled some 560 kilometers from the
western town of Bergama, staged a sit-down demonstration on the
bridge to express their opposition against the using of cyanide in
a gold mine in Bergama.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators carried banners saying "No to cyanide use
untile we die," and they left the bridge peacefully after warnings
by police.
</P>
<P>
Eurogold, a company owned by France, Australia and Canada, has
been said to use cyanide in the gold processing in the gold mines
in Bergama.
</P>
<P>
Local villagers feared that the cyanide will damage the
environment of the historic town, where the ancient relics attract
thousands of tourists.
</P>
<P>
The company experts, however, stated that the villages have
been misled by the environmentalists and the method of using
cyanide to process gold is safe.
</P>
<P>
A Bergama court is reportedly reviewing the application from
the protesters calling for a ban on the possible use of cyanide
in the gold mine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
