<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Block PKK Bases in Black Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish police chief said
today that the Turkish troops and police will prevent the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) from establishing new bases
in Turkey's Black Sea region
</P>
<P>
Necati Bilican, General Director of Police Forces of Turkey,
made the remarks in a meeting with a visiting senior police
delegation from Moldova, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Bilican said that the PKK rebels had long been locked in
eastern and southeastern Turkey and they now wanted to expand
their activities to the Black Sea region.
</P>
<P>
"We have organized groups in the Black Sea region who have
had special training in combating terrorism," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security troops have been fighting the PKK since
the Kurdish armed group start their independent movement in
1984.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has increased its cooperation with neighboring
countries like Iran, Moldova, Armenia, Georgia as well as Russia
in order to prevent the PKK from receiving outside support,
according to Bilican.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Ismet Sezgin said last
weekend that the government will lift the 10-year-old emergency
rule in southeastern Turkey by early next year.
</P>
<P>
He said that this move was made because the task of fighting
the PKK has been basically completed and there is no need to
keep the emergency rule in these areas.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has long been termed as the most dangerous threat to
the border security of southeastern Turkey, leading to a massive
cross-border military operation by the Turkish troops in
northern Iraq in mid-May this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 27,000 people, including PKK rebels, civilians and
government troops, have been killed in conflicts since the PKK
started a separatist war in order to establish an independent
Kurdish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
