<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coordinator for Iraqi Aid: "Oil-For-Food" Plan a </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Staffan de Mistura, the
outgoing coordinator for Iraqi aid in Baghdad, said today the "oil
for food" plan was a success despite early delays.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference to formally present his
successor Denis Halliday, De Mistura said, "A total of 1.3 million
tons of food and medicines which have arrived inside Iraq have,
according to all indications we have, reached the ordinary Iraqis
affected by sanctions."
</P>
<P>
De Mistura said that the 142 U.N. observers inside Iraq have
been able to move freely without major impediment, keeping tabs on
some 53,000 retail centers and ensuring equal distribution to the
Iraqis and Kurdish population in the northern reaches of the
country.
</P>
<P>
He said that there had been some disagreements with the Iraqi
government. "But we were able to solve them, perhaps by discussing
in a firm and fair way on both sides," he added.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator said the full allotment of food and medicine
purchased from the first 2 billion U.S. dollars, which ran from
December to June, would continue arriving through the middle of
November.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been allowed since last year to sell oil under the
"oil-for-food" plan, mainly to buy food and medicine for its
people suffering under sanctions imposed by the U.N. in 1990 after
it invaded Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The second round of the plan, which allows Iraq to sell another
2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil, will run from June to
December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
