<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lasting Peace Still Distance Away in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Despite peace initiatives
with the Somali warlords in and outside the country through both
local and foreign diplomatic channels, a lasting peace for the
war-ravaged country is still some distance away.
</P>
<P>
However, after seven years of anarchy and lawlessness,
traditional leaders, sultans and Imams from eleven regions have
met in south Mogadishu with the intention of peace mediating
among the various Somali clans.
</P>
<P>
More than 160 traditional delegates representing 14 clans and
sub-clans have concluded a 30-day meeting here in the Somali
capital. The elders have made an appeal to all the Somalis to
reconcile and settle their disputes through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Ugas Abdullahi Ugas Farah, one of the central Galgudud region
traditional leaders, has called the leaders of the social groups
for a conference aimed at discussing the current situation of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Ugas Farah who did not mention a venue for such a conference
said, his clan is ready to invest any such conference if the
Somali traditional leaders agree upon its convening and venue.
</P>
<P>
An appeal made by the elders has condemned what they called
the deliberate attacks and territorial violations by the
Ethiopian government against the Somalis and called on the
Ethiopian troops to pull out of Gedo region unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Addis said they entered the area in hot pursuit of Islamic
fundamentalists who allegedly crossed over to attack Ethiopians.
</P>
<P>
The elders also called for international relief agencies to
help displaced refugees caused by the Ethiopian "invasion" in
southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The Hirab community traditional leaders at Ramadan hotel also
made an appeal particularly to the people in Benadir region of
Mogadishu to stop the widespread looting and kidnaping in the
streets of the capital.
</P>
<P>
In response to this, the north Mogadishu authorities have
announced a new peace campaign.
</P>
<P>
Jafar Sheikh Mohamud Mohamed, Attorney General of the north
Mogadishu Islamic courts, said all the Islamic courts militiamen
will be involved in the new peace efforts in north Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed called on the people to collaborate with the Islamic
militiamen for the common good of the Somalis. The north
Mogadishu Islamic courts have been dormant ever since Sheikh Ali
Sheikh Mohamud was sacked from the post of the chairmanship in a
decree issued by Ali Mahdi Mohamed in October last year. Sheikh
Ali was reinstated.
</P>
<P>
These new peace tentative among the Somalis are taking place
amid new speculations on whether an anticipated reconciliation
conference in the northeastern region of Bossaso in November this
year will take place.
</P>
<P>
People believe that there will be no real settlement unless a
concrete agreement is reached among all factions in Mogadishu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0054 </DOCNO>
