<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls for UN's Help to Approve Food Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today urged the
U.N. Sanctions Committee to persuade the United States and Britain
to approve the deals that Iraq has signed with foreign countries
under the first stage of oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the chairman of the sanctions committee, Iraqi
Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed Al-Sahhaf said that despite the
elapse of more than two months since the end of the first phase of
the deal, more than 60 contracts which were signed in the first
phase, are still frozen, Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
These contracts even haven't reached to the members of the
committee, Al-Sahhaf said.
</P>
<P>
He asked the committee to take necessary measures to accelerate
the implementation of the contracts as Iraq has already started
concluding deals on the purchase of foodstuffs and medicines under
the second phase of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal, which was signed in May last year and
went into effect last December, allows Iraq to sell 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil in six months for badly needed food and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council renewed the deal on June 8 for
another six months, allowing Iraq to sell another 2 billion
dollars of oil.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has always been accusing the United States and Britain,
which are members of the committee, of blocking the implementation
of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The contracts signed between Iraq and other countries must be
anonymously approved by the members of the sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the INA reported that Al-Sahhaf sent messages to the
foreign ministers of the states whose deals with Iraq were blocked
by Britain or the U.S. in the first phase of the deal.
</P>
<P>
As-Sahhaf appealed to the foreign ministers of these states to
contact Washington and London and urge them to lift their
suspension of the deals.
</P>
<P>
He also urged them to make greater efforts to end this abnormal
situation and serve the interests of their countries in Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
