<HEADLINE> Hungarian Diver Wins Men's One-meter Springboard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MESSINA, Sicily, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Unknown Imre Lengyel of
Hungary stole the limelight of Tuesday's diving competition by winning
the men's one-meter springboard title.
</P>
<P>
Lengyel, who finished second in the preliminary but surged ahead in
the semi-finals, again beat his strongest opponent Wang Tianling of
China in the final.
</P>
<P>
He collected 75.60 and 79.20 points from his fourth and fifth
dives, the two highest scores of Tuesday's competitions, to collect a
total of 407.85 points for the title.
</P>
<P>
Wang, China's national champion of the event, managed only a 74.70
points from his sixth and last dive of the final.
</P>
<P>
His first dive, a forward two and a half samersaults at tuck
position, earned him only 51.06 points. The poor scoring eventually
cost him the gold.
</P>
<P>
Wang's total of 400.41 was 7.44 points behind Lengyel. Chris
Lepoole of Canada took the bronze medal at 384.36 points.
</P>
<P>
Evan Stewart of Zimbabwe, who won the event at the 1994 Rome World
Championships, finished a disappointing fifth with a total of 354.66.
</P>
<P>
The men's one-meter springboard is the second event of the
Universiade diving tournament. On Monday, China finished one-two in
the women's one-meter springboard through Lu Haisong and Chen Lixia.
</P>
</TEXT>
