<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo and his Egyptian counterpart Amre Moussa
signed a joint communique in Pretoria today, both pledging to
promote bilateral cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Nzo and Moussa discussed ways and means to
enhance cooperation in the fields of data and information
exchange, the use of the information super-highway as well as the
establishment of an electronic network.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, five bilateral agreements dealing
with tourism, science and technology, arts and culture, double
taxation and air services, were signed at the second session of
the joint commission.
</P>
<P>
Several other agreements were also initialed. The two sides
are currently working toward the finalization of these accords,
which will promote trade and economic ties, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
On the international front, the two ministers expressed
support for the formation of an African peace-keeping force. They
also urged all parties involved in the conflicts in Congo, Sierra
Leone, Angola and Somalia to seek peaceful solutions to their
problems.
</P>
<P>
Showing great concern over the escalation of conflicts in the
Middle East between Israel and the Palestinians, the ministers
called on Israel to cease settlement activities in the occupied
Palestinian territories and to dismantle existing colonies.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also told the press today that Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, who is keen to travel to South Africa, would visit the
country in the near future. 
