<HEADLINE> US-DPRK Missile Talks Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Talks between the United
States and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on
missile sales, originally scheduled to be held today in New York,
have been postponed, a State Department official said today.
</P>
<P>
"The talks have been postponed," he said. He would not say
who postponed the talks and when they would be resumed.
</P>
<P>
Other administration officials said DPRK diplomats in New York
simply gave notice that they were returning to Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
The postponement came one day after the State Department
announced that two DPRK diplomats were given asylum in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The State Department said Tuesday the U.S. move to give asylum
to Chang Sung-gil, ambassador to Egypt, and his brother Chang
Sung-ho, a diplomat in Paris, would not affect the three-day
missile talks. 
</P>
