<HEADLINE> First Land Auction Since Handover Nets HK$ 5.67 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The first land auction in Hong
Kong since the handover brought in 5.67 billion HK dollars
(727 million US dollars) to the coffins of the Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government today.
</P>
<P>
Three government lots, all designated for private residential
use, were put up for auction this afternoon, with the largest site
in Repulse Bay sold for 5.55 billion HK dollars (712 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Located in the south coast of the Hong Kong Island and
commanding a good view of the Repulse Bay, the 10,570 square meter
plot was finally sold to Gain Regent Development Limited after a
string of keen bidding among property developers opened at 3
billion HK dollars (385 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Property analysts predicted that with a plot ratio of three,
the Repulse Bay site could offer up to 31,710 square meters of
gross floor area.
</P>
<P>
Two other small low-density residential sites were also
auctioned off today, one in Lamma Island for 64 million HK dollars
(8 million US dollars) and the other in Sha Tin for 56 million HK
dollars (7 million US dollars). The two plots have a total area
of nearly 5,200 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Today's land auction was the start of a series of government
land sales over the next few years. Last month, the SAR government
announced a five-year land sales program, which would release
about 378 hectares of residential land.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa was determined to provide 85,000
residential units each year, in an effort to solve the widely
concerned housing problem.
</P>
<P>
Acting Financial Secretary Kwong Ki Chi said today: "Between
now and March 1999, we will be putting out another 31 sites
totaling 63 hectares of low-density residential land to meet the
market demand."
</P>
<P>
"We should not read too much into the results of a single
auction," he responded to media inquires on the outcome of the
first land sales.  
</P>
</TEXT>
