<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Woman Discovered in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Le Thi Co, a 117-year-old
Vietnamese woman living in suburb of Ho Chi Minh city, is believed
to be the oldest woman in the world, Vietnam news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Co may break the record held by a 116-year-old Canadian woman
who was recognized by the Guinness world records, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Co's identity card issued in 1961 showed that she was born in
1880 in Plong, a province in southern Vietnam. Now she lives in
Hoc Mon district of Ho Chi Minh city.
</P>
<P>
She has about 500 living relatives, spreading over five
generations, said Pham Van Lo, Co's 10th son who is 65 years old.
</P>
<P>
Co, who had 14 children, lost her husband in 1960. Her oldest
child died two years ago at the age of 82. Her youngest child is
now 59.
</P>
<P>
Co's father lived 99 years and her youngest sister is 95 now.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Co cannot move out of her house because of pain
caused by a fall but her eyes and ears are in good condition. With
a good memory, she can remember her wedding party and the groom's
wedding gifts.
</P>
<P>
Asked if she was beautiful when she was young, Co said, "Just
normal, like other girls."
</P>
<P>
She said her children and grand-children usually give her
money.
</P>
<P>
"But I don't take much because I'm old and they are young. They
need money more than I do," she explained.
</P>
<P>
Co said the key to her longevity was manual labor and a
moderate diet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
