<HEADLINE> Bundesbank Sells Dlrs to Defend German Mark: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Germany's central bank, the
Bundesbank, has sold an estimated 3.5 billion U.S. dollars since
mid-June to stem the steep decline of the German mark on money
markets, said German economists today.
</P>
<P>
The market interventions, combined with threats from senior
central bankers to raise interest rates, had helped to lower the
dollar value from its peak of 1.8873 marks registered on August 6
to the current levels of around 1.80 marks, said the economists at
Germany's largest commercial bank, the Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that as a result of the intervention, the
Bundesbank's reserves had declined from 72.8 billion marks in the
first week of June to the current 68.0 billion marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
