<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Further Raises Banks' Liquidity Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank today
raised anew the liquidity reserves requirement for banks from 5
percent to 8 percent in order to stabilize the exchange rate
between the Philippine peso and the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to siphon off more than 30 billion pesos
(1 billion U.S. dollars) in excess liquidity from the monetary
system, local television reports quoted officials at the Central
Bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank, meanwhile, announced a one-percentage-point
increase in banks' legal stationary reserves from 13 percent to 14
percent effective today.
</P>
<P>
The liquidity reserves are the deposits which should be
invested in short-term government securities issued by the Central
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Banks are also required to keep some of its deposits just in
vaults or deposit them with the Central Bank with a very low
interest rate.
</P>
<P>
The measures to raise both the two kinds of bank reserves came
after the peso suffered a new round of speculative attacks these
days.
</P>
<P>
The peso, which began to jitter again last week, today
depreciated sharply to the dollar at the local currency market,
with its average exchange rate against the dollar plunging to
30.234 pesos to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
This latest exchange rate was the lowest since the currency's
de facto depreciation allowed by the Central Bank on July 11.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank today also was forced to intervene in the
currency market for the first time in two weeks, selling about 10
million dollars at a rate of 30.05 pesos to one dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
