<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Chief Urges Continued Peace Efforts on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Burundi peace efforts
must continue despite the failure of talks facilitated by
Tanzania's former president J. Nyerere and scheduled for August 25
in Arusha, northern Tanzanian, the OAU chief has said.
</P>
<P>
Salim A. Salim, secretary general of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), made the appeal in an interview with local
press in Arusha on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was unfortunate that the Burundian government
delegation boycotted the meeting but it is still his hope that
"negotiations must go on and there is need for further
consultations to determine the way forward."
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the failed talks, Salim stressed there is no
alternative to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"I think the conditions for peace talks were fair, but the
Burundian government feels differently. I think that we'll have
to listen also to what they think is the way forward," Salim
said.
</P>
<P>
Salim said that the OAU will continue to consult to bring back
Major Pierre Buyoya's military government of Burundi into the
talks.
</P>
<P>
The OAU will try to overcome bottlenecks that exist now in the
peace talks, said Salim, adding that "all of us can only help to
start talks. No one can impose on the people of Burundi...It's
only the Burundians who can decide on their destiny."
</P>
<P>
The scheduled all-party talks on Burundi aborted after Major
Buyoya's military government refused to take part in the talks on
alleged grounds that they were insecure in Tanzania and that the
peace facilitator Nyerere was partially favoring the Hutus.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, however, dismissed the allegations, saying that he
has been making sincere efforts to bring peace to the war-torn
central African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
