<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 50 Cyclists Receive Blood-test at World Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A total of 50 cyclists received
random blood tests in Perth, Australia, on Wednesday, the opening
day of the World Cycling Track Championships.
</P>
<P>
It marked the first time that blood-test was conducted at a
world cycling championship.
</P>
<P>
UCI, world cycling's governing body, became the first world
sports ruling organization to supply both urine-test and
blood-test samples. UCI started to take blood samples from road
riders this year at the European competitions.
</P>
<P>
UCI is attempting to employ blood-test to crack down the use of
Erythropoietin (EPO) among cyclists, which could increase the
number of red blood cells and therefore boost endurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
