<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Reserves Decline Sharply in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign-exchange
reserves are expected to fall below the 30 billion U.S. dollar
mark next month, raising fears that the country may face a serious
foreign-exchange crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to a tally released by the Bank of Korea (BOK), the
nation's foreign-exchange holdings fell from 33.7 billion
U.S. dollars to 31.5 billion dollars today.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) recommends that a
country's foreign-exchange holdings remain equivalent to the value
of its imports for three months.
</P>
<P>
Considering this, experts say, South Korea's present holdings
fall below that internationally-recognized optimum level with the
country's reserves being now of a value equivalent to imports of a
mere 2.6 months.
</P>
<P>
The sharp decline was mainly due to the central bank's active
intervention to curb the falling won-dollar rates, and its
extension of emergency foreign currency-denominated loans to
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The central bank had to extend 1.2 billion dollars as special
loans to protect banks' external credit standing, and sell 800
million dollars to stablize the foreign-exchange market during the
turmoil of depreciation of won.
</P>
<P>
The won-dollar exchange rate, which fell rapidly from 840 level
by the end of last year to 897.50 on August 18 and 904.60 today,
is feared to drop further.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the central bank plans to extend more than 1
billion dollars in foreign currency-denominated loans to domestic
financial institutions next month when Japanese financiers usually
withdraw their loans extended to Korean banks to settle their
accounts.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts say that the government should immediately
employ appropriate measures to secure sufficient foreign-exchange
holdings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
