<HEADLINE> Shanghai Begins Construction of World's Tallest Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a 94-storey
skyscraper, believed to the world's tallest, commenced today in
Shanghai and scheduled for completion in the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The 460-meter tall Shanghai World Financial Center, which will
be built at a cost 960 million US dollars, will be jointly funded
by Mori Building Co. Ltd., the Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund
of Japan, and 34 Japanese and US financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The office and hotel facility, located in the Lujiazui
Financial and Trade Zone in Shanghai's Pudong New Area, was
designed by US architectural firm, KPF.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai World Financial Center will be eight meters taller
than the Petronas Twin Towers in Kuala Lumper, Malaysia, the
current record-holder at 451.9 meters.
</P>
<P>
The 443-meter Sears Tower in Chicago is currently the second
tallest building in the world, with the 88-storey Jinmao Building
currently under construction in the Pudong New Area ranking third
at 421 meters. 
