Republic Denis Sassou Nguesso said today his successor Pascal
Lissouba hired foreign mercenaries in air aid on his home
districts.
</P>
<P>
"Russian or Croatian mercenaries flew from Pointe-Noire these
helicopters which sowed desolation in the districts of northern
Brazzaville and in the populated areas. This is a real genocide,
to say the least," said Sassou Nguesso in an interview with Radio
France Internationale.
</P>
<P>
Four Russian-made MI-18 and MI-24 Combat helicopters pounded
Sassou Nguesso's Mpila home district in the capital of Brazzaville
early on Tuesday. It was the first time helicopters joined the
three-month fray.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse reported that the helicopters also bombed
the streets around Tower Nabemba, a 30-story skyscraper belonging
to the Elf-Aquitaine oil group of France, before flying back to
the Pointe-Noire, a port city southwest Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
France, the Central African country's former colonial power,
condemned the bombing on Tuesday, saying it might bring a civil
war to the whole country.
</P>
<P>
Fighting began on June 5 after Lissouba tried to disarm his
rival Sassou Nguesso ahead of a now postponed elections.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Gabon's capital Libreville said mediation efforts
remained suspended, after representatives from Lissouba failed to
show up on Tuesday. Envoys of Sassou Nguesso were waiting in
Libreville. 
</P>
