<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Club Donates to Blind Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- More than 1.75 million blind
Chinese may once again see the light of day due to a treatment
program sponsored by Lions Clubs International and the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
Lions Clubs International Foundation (LCIF) granted 15.3
million US dollars today to fund operations for 1.75 million
people suffering from cataracts, the establishment of ophthalmic
clinics in 100 Chinese county-level hospitals, and the training of
4,000 ophthalmologists in cataract surgery.
</P>
<P>
The foundation made the donation as part of the program known
as "SightFirst China Action".
</P>
<P>
Deng Pufang, chairman of the China Disabled Persons Federation,
and Howard Patterson Jr., president of Lions Clubs International,
signed the agreement in the Great Hall of the People here today.
</P>
<P>
According to State Councillor Peng Peiyun, who also attended
the signing ceremony, "The program will help restore eyesight to a
large number of blind Chinese."
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, it will greatly enhance the surgical skills
of Chinese ophthalmologists," said Peng, who is also Chairperson
of the State Council Coordinating Committee on Disabilities.
</P>
<P>
China is home to more than nine million blind people, nearly
half of whom are suffering from cataracts. Chinese ophthalmologists
have completed an untold number of cataract operations since
1988. However, limited economic conditions and medical facilities
in rural China cannot control the increase of cataract patients.
</P>
<P>
"SightFirst China Action" will help China correct treatable
cases of blindness over the next five years, and will give the
gift of sight to more than 1.75 million Chinese, particularly in
the country's poorest rural regions.
</P>
<P>
Lions Clubs International, established in 1917, is the world's
largest humanitarian service organization. The foundation has
carried its worldwide "SightFirst" program for the past six years,
including the largest donation in China this time.
</P>
<P>
According to Patterson, "Lions Clubs builds bridges of
understanding between themselves and people around the world by
funding humanitarian projects."
</P>
<P>
Wu Jieping, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of China's
National People's Congress; He Luli, vice-chairman of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference; and Chinese Minister of Health Chen Minzhang also
attended the ceremony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
