<HEADLINE> Russian, Ukrainian FMs Meet on Border Demarcation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Ukraine said here
today that they will shelve the demarcation of their mutual border
for the time being.
</P>
<P>
"It is not an issue for today, to put it mildly," Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said at a press conference after
meeting with his Ukrainian counterpart, Gennady Udovenko.
</P>
<P>
"It will make the resolution of many issues considerably
easier," Primakov said, adding that both sides attach great
importance to bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
However, Primakov and Udovenko did sign a statement on the
legal aspects of the border issue, Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko arrived here Tuesday evening and is expected to leave
here tonight.
</P>
<P>
Interfax said determination of the border on the map is under
way following direct orders from Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
On a separate issue, Primakov reiterated Moscow's "negative
reaction" to the multinational navy exercise code-named Sea
Breeze '97 currently being held in the vicinity of the Crimean
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
He said according to the initial scenario, turmoil began in a
country due to assistance to separatist forces granted by a
neighboring country, but the scenario was hurriedly changed to
include an earthquake after Russia told Americans it was
absolutely unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Moscow does not like the new scenario either, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the two ministers also discussed bilateral
trade and economic cooperation, a top priority in their
relations. 
</P>
