<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Population Growth Remains Slow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Population growth in China
remained slow in the five years since the 14th national congress
of the Communist Party of China (CPC) in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The State Statistics Bureau (SSB) reports that the population
on the mainland was 1,223.89 million at the end of 1996, and the
birth rate and population growth rate had dropped to 16.98 per
thousand and 10.42 per thousand, respectively, the lowest since
the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
According to the SSB, average population growth was 10.95 per
thousand over the past five years, with the population increasing
by 13.05 million annually.
</P>
<P>
China hit a peak around 1990, and population growth in coming
years should be lower. That peak was the third since 1949.
</P>
<P>
The SSB said that, in the past five years, the education level
in China improved thanks to increased spending on cultural
development and social welfare.
</P>
<P>
For every 100,000 people, there were 2,040 college grads and
28,796 junior middle school grads by the end of 1996, compared
with 1,422 and 23,344 in 1990, up 43.46 percent and 23.36 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990-1996 period, the number of people with secondary
middle school and primary school educations increased 7.18 percent
and 1.95 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the number of dropouts declined a great deal. There
were 18.36 million children aged 6 to 14 who left school before
completing nine years of the compulsory education, a decrease of
44 percent from the 1990 figure.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, 18.62 percent of the 6- to 14-year-olds were unable to
attend class, and that dropped to 8.83 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
There were 145.43 million illiterates above the age of 15 in
1995, a decrease of 36.18 million from the 1990 figure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
