<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth in Domestic Credit Slows Down in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The growth in net domestic credit
in the Philippines slowed down by nearly 10 percentage points
during the first four months this year compared with the same
period last year, the Philippine Central Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
In a report to President Fidel Ramos, the bank said net
domestic credit to both the public and private sectors reached
nearly 1.54 trillion pesos (51.5 billion U.S. dollars) during the
first four months this year, posting a 24.3 percent rise from the
year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
But this latest growth figure showed a sharp decline from the
34.2 percent recorded in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
The private sector continued to get the bulk of loans,
accounting for 78.7 percent, extended by the country's monetary
system during the period.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year growth of private sector credit, however,
declined to 36.8 percent by the end of April, after peaking at 56
percent in August last year.
</P>
<P>
During the period, credits for the private sector reached 1.21
trillion pesos (40.5 billion dollars), coming mainly from
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector continued to be the main recipient of
the domestic credit for the period under review, accounting for
29.3 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
