<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Pulls Out of U.N. Rights Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) has pulled out of a U.N. human rights treaty,
saying it has abused the "sovereignty and dignity of the socialist
and third world countries", a DPRK official said today.
</P>
<P>
Han Chang-on, DPRK's deputy permanent representative to the
United Nations in Geneva, told a news conference that his
government was quitting the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights.
</P>
<P>
DPRK was accused of human rights violations in a resolution
passed last Friday by a U.N. human rights sub-commission. Members
drafting the resolution were from France, Norway, Greece, the
United States, Belgium and Columbia. The sub-commission is an
expert body.
</P>
<P>
Han criticized the United States and other western forces for
"groundlessly selecting and attacking those countries that are not
obedient to them and do not follow their political mode, and on
the contrary, they ignore or cover with the so-called 'democratic
umbrella' the grave human rights violations in their own countries
and their allies".
</P>
<P>
Han said Pyongyang sent a letter of withdrawal to the
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi A. Annan on August 25. It joined the
rights treaty in 1981.
</P>
<P>
He also said the DPRK delegation will not attend the 16th
session of the Committee on the Rights of the Child.
</P>
<P>
"Our government will not, in the future, either, tolerate any
attempts to impair our sovereignty and stifle our socialist
system, under the pretext of 'protection of human rights', and
will take further resolute counter-measures to those attempts,"
said the DPRK official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
