<HEADLINE> South Korea Seeks Direct Inter-Korean Air Routes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government is
stepping-up its efforts to conclude an agreement with the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on opening direct
inter-Korean air routes, according to government officials.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that Seoul has been trying to sign the pact as
soon as possible because its national flag carriers will be able
to benefit from the accord by saving considerable time and costs.
</P>
<P>
"We want to resume the talks about establishing direct
inter-Korean air routes at an earliest possible date," Kim
Kwang-jae, a director of the Ministry of Construction and
Transportation said today.
</P>
<P>
The next round of meeting will likely be held next month, he
said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea and the DPRK, which have banned each other's
national flag carriers from passing through their skies since the
nation was divided in 1945, have been holding meetings under the
mediation of International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO)
since last September.
</P>
<P>
At previous meetings, the two sides agreed in principle to open
their flight information regions (FIRs) to each other, but failed
to reach a final conclusion as the talks ran into a deadlock over
the establishment of a direct network for the communication of
flight information.
</P>
<P>
At present, South Korean airplanes flying the Seoul-North
American, Seoul-Khabarovsk as well as Seoul-Vladiostok routes have
to detour the DPRK's FIR, thus flying an unnecessarily longer
route. 
</P>
</TEXT>
