<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Seeks Japan's Support on Greenhouse Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Australia today sought Japan's
support for its position on climate change, arguing it would be in
both countries' economic interests to oppose binding greenhouse
gas emission targets for developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made today by Australian Primary Industries and
Energy Minister John Anderson while addressing the Australia-Japan
Symposium in Canberra.
</P>
<P>
In the lead-up to December's global greenhouse gas conference
in Kyoto, Japan, Anderson said it was in both Japan's and
Australia's interests to stand firm against global pressure and
oppose binding greenhouse gas emission reduction targets in Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
Anderson tried to persuade Japan by saying that "Over the next
decade, Australia should emerge as easily the biggest supplier of
primary energy to Japan."
</P>
<P>
He said Australia was set to meet a massive increase in
Japanese demand for resources, particularly energy. Australia so
far remains Japan's major energy supplier, exporting more than
half of the coal Japan imports annually.
</P>
<P>
Anderson said Australia could potentially sell an additional
740 million U.S. dollars of steaming coal a year to Japan, and an
extra 1.11 billion U.S. dollars of liquefied natural gas in 10
years.
</P>
<P>
But Japan appears to be unlikely to support Australia. During
his visit earlier this year to Australia, Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto disappointed his Australian counterpart John
Howard by declining to express Japan's support over Australia's
greenhouse gas stands.
</P>
<P>
Australia remains isolated on the issue and has failed to win
support from the United State and the European Union (EU) despite
great lobbying efforts.
</P>
<P>
The EU wants all developed countries to reduce their greenhouse
gas emissions by 15 percent of their 1990 level by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Australia argues that as the world's leading coal exporter,
dependent on greenhouse gas-producing fossil fuels, it stands to
lose more than other countries if it adopted the EU proposals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Unchanged in July in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 28 (Xinhua) -- Inflation rate in the Philippines
remained unchanged at 4.8 percent in July as compared with the
same month last year, the Philippine Central Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
On a month-to-month basis, the inflation rate rose by only 0.1
percent in July, representing a slowdown in the rise compared with
a 1.3-percent increase in June, according to figures released by
the bank.
</P>
<P>
The average inflation rate for the first seven months stood at
4.7 percent, well below the whole-year target of 6 to 7 percent
under the economic program supported by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Among the commodities, the prices of food, beverage and
tobacco, fuel, light and water registered lower rates in July.
</P>
<P>
Because of the favorable trend in price movements, the Central
Bank said, the operating targets for base money (BM) and reserve
money (RM) continued to be below the targeted ceilings set by the
IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
