<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expanding Labor Market (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- China's rapid economic growth
has offered greater job opportunities, promoted the
market-oriented distribution of labor resources and provided
wide-ranging options for both employers and job-hunters.
</P>
<P>
China's GDP has grown by 77 percent over the past five years. A
rapidly expanding economic scale has contributed to higher
employment figures, according to a recent State Statistical Bureau
report.
</P>
<P>
China had more than 680 million employees by the end of last
year, up 6.3 percent from 1991. Some 30 million jobs were added in
urban areas due to the fact that governments and society as a
whole paid special attention to employment.
</P>
<P>
People have abandoned the formerly common practice of relying
on government for job assignments, and are instead attempting to
find employment on their own. Graduates, former soliders and
redundant workers have turned to the market for jobs.
</P>
<P>
While the government's role in the effort has weakened
somewhat, it is nonetheless actively drafting policies and
providing services to cultivate and promote labor market.
</P>
<P>
As a result, job placement services have mushroomed over the
past five years with 31,000 related agencies in place at the end
of 1996. The various agencies offered job opportunities for 8.9
million people last year alone, in addition to offering various
training programs for almost another four million people.
</P>
<P>
The competing systems of multiple choice and free transfers in
employment have enabled employers to select superior workers for
their labor forces, while employees now have the freedom to seek
higher paying positions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expanding Labor Market (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some four percent of the total number of urban employees moved
elsewhere during 1996. a figure which would have been
substantially larger had resignations and contract suspensions
been included, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 million rural laborers are currently seeking jobs
in urban areas, while over nine million urbanites are working in
rural township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the universally accepted labor contract system has
 further defined the rights and interests of employers and
workers, and in turn has helped form a healthy labor market.
</P>
<P>
Some 75 million employees were working under contract at the
end of last year, up 184 percent on the 1991 level. The former
figure accounted for slightly over half the total of employees in
the country, while the ratio approached 70 percent in state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that one outstanding characteristic of China's
labor market development lies in the private sector. Some 37
million laborers have found employment with private businesses
since 1991, a figure equivalent to 91.2 percent of the national
total increase in the number of employees.
</P>
<P>
The private sector has gained increasing importance as an
employment source for the large number of workers declared
redundant by state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
China's registered unemployment rate for 1996 was three
percent, up 0.7 percentage points on 1991. The report concluded
that employment pressures will become even more tense as
enterprise continue to adopt reform measures for trimming payrolls
and improving efficiency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
