<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Set to Join Talks on Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein is expected to be
invited to join all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland
this week after security chiefs confirmed that the Irish
Republican Army (IRA) had maintained its ceasefire for nearly six
weeks, The Daily Telegraph reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The invitation is expected to be confirmed on Thursday when
Marjorie Mowlam, secretary of state for Northern Ireland, meets
Prime Minister Tony Blair at Downing Street to brief him on the
security situation.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein is the political arm of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
Blair will embark on a new round of meetings with leaders of
Northern Ireland's main political parties ahead of the talks'
resumption next month, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Ministers said at the time of the latest ceasefire, on July 20,
that if it was not breached for six weeks Sinn Fein would be
invited to join the negotiations that start on Sept 15.
</P>
<P>
A formal announcement could take place on Thursday after the
Downing Street meeting - four days before the formal end of the
six-week period - for "administrative reasons". 
</P>
</TEXT>
