<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unusual Ways of Burial Found in Ancient Kingdom Site in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A baby buried in an alcove of a
cave and another cave full of bodies and skeletons dating back
hundreds of years have been found on the site of the Guge Kingdom
in the western part of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists say the find is important because very
few ancient tomb burials have been found in Tibet, which is famous
for its sky burial where bodies are left on a bier outside,
exposed to birds of prey.
</P>
<P>
They also say that the baby buried in an alcove is the first to
have been found in China and speculate that the parents hated to
bury their child far away, because according to rule children's
bodies could not be buried in the tribal cemetery. So, they buried
their child in their home or nearby.
</P>
<P>
The cave full of bodies and skeletons is on a cliff. The
remains are of some 30 persons, though whether they were nobles or
ordinary people, and were buried according to a normal system or
as some form of punishment, are yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
The site of the kingdom is located in the Ali region some 5,000
meters above sea level. It is famous for its temples and grottos
with breath-taking wall paintings dating from the 10th to the 17th
Century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
