<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electronic Pets Banned in Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The State Education Commission
(SEC) today issued a ban on electronic "pets" in schools, four
days before the fall semester starts on September 1.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people by the thousands, both kids and adults, have
been caught up in the craze over the small hand-held devices for
cats, chickens, dogs and dinosaurs, which can tell their owners
when they are hungry, sleepy or want to be entertained via a tiny
electronic screen.
</P>
<P>
The pets, which recently have become available in markets, have
had a negative influence on students' studies and the order in
some schools, an SEC official said.
</P>
<P>
To keep students' attention on their studies and improve school
administration, a circular issued by the SEC prohibits students
from taking the devices to school. SEC also will conduct a series
of educational activities to help students recognize the
disadvantages of the electronic pets, he said.
</P>
<P>
SEC will also formulate a regulation under which any of the
pets found at school will be confiscated, and children who take
the pets to exams will have their test scores canceled.
</P>
<P>
The circular also prohibits business people from marketing the
electronic pets, electronic game machines, other kinds of toys and
costly stationery to schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
