<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Securities Officials Confident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Securities officials from Hong
Kong said that they are confident in the ongoing success of the
securities market of Hong Kong after its return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The listing of shares issued by inland companies or by
companies with inland business ties will not produce any negative
effects but rather increase choices and opportunities for
investors, Alec Tsui, chief executive of the Stock Exchange of
Hong Kong, said in an interview with Xinhua during the ongoing
Ninth PACAP Finance Conference here.
</P>
<P>
The capitalization of the stock market of Hong Kong has reached
590 billion US dollars, the sixth largest in the world and the
second largest in Asia, Tsui said, adding that daily transactions
averaged 1.7 billion US dollars in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
He noted that of the 622 listed companies, 34 are from inland
areas. He revealed that starting from September, the Hang Seng
Stock Index will include a sub-index for red chips stocks from the
inland companies.
</P>
<P>
After its return to the motherland, Hong Kong will continue to
serve as a bridge between the overseas and inland markets, Tsui
said.
</P>
<P>
Ivers W. Riley, chief executive of the Hong Kong Futures
Exchange Ltd., said that a mature and growing Hong Kong economy
will be able to meet the challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The development of the Hong Kong stock market will eventually
improve the capability of the inland areas to attract overseas
investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Laura M. Cha, a member of the Commission and Executive Director
of the Securities and Futures Commission of Hong Kong, expressed
the hope that all companies listed in Hong Kong will strictly
abide by laws and rules to ensure market confidence and
prosperity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
