<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Lifts Levy on Property Purchase by Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government
has decided to lift, effective from tomorrow, the levy imposed on
the purchase of properties by foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made by the cabinet today, Malaysian Deputy
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia imposed 20 months ago a levy of 100,000 ringgit (about
35,714 U.S. dollars) on each purchase of properties above 250,000
ringgit (about 89,285 dollars) by foreign nationals with an
initial aim to control foreign ownership of properties in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said, "It is the low and medium-cost houses that we want
to protect, but they can buy the rest because there is supply for
that now."
</P>
<P>
For properties below 250,000 ringgit, foreign buyers would
require clearance from the local authorities, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Provinces to Charge Extra Fees on Tobacco Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese provinces and
Shanghai Municipality have decided to charge extra fees for
tobacco products to fund smoking controls and healthcare
campaigns, according to a senior official with the Ministry of
Health (MOH).
</P>
<P>
China has never before issued such fees on tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
Hubei Province will pioneer the move, collecting four percent
of the sales of local tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Province and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region have
also worked out plans for the use of the extra fees in their own
health promotion drives.
</P>
<P>
"When there aren't central regulations in this field yet, these
areas have set good examples for the whole country," Cai Renhua,
director of the MOH's Health Policy and Law Department, told
Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
He said the new measure "kills two birds with one stone."
</P>
<P>
"It can on one hand curb the increase of sales of tobacco. On
the other hand, it can fund smoking-control campaigns and solve
financial problems in health care work," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Studies made in 1993 by the Health Economics Institute showed
that if an additional fee of 0.1 yuan was added to each pack of
cigarettes, the state would collect a total of eight billion yuan
(about one billion US dollars) -- the figure set for the national
health budget for that year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that China's tobacco industry produced 1.7
trillion cigarettes in 1996. The country's 320 million smokers
puffed away on 4.8 billion cigarettes per day, or 240 million
packs.
</P>
<P>
The colossal industry has been a major source for China's
revenue since 1987. It turned out 83 billion yuan (about 10
billion US dollars) in revenue in 1996, five times that of 1986,
according to a report from the Chinese Academy of Preventive
Medicine (CAPM).
</P>
<P>
Experts say that adding extra charges on tobacco products and
using the money to promote good health is an effective plan used
in many countries to control smoking.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the 10th World Conference on Tobacco or Health
have agreed that the measure should be further spread in China to
combat tobacco-related illnesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heart-controlled Mobile Phone Under Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at British Telecom
(BT) are developing new mobile phones that will automatically
alert a hospital if their owner's heart rate or blood pressure
reaches dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
The phones will also be able to show where the person is on an
electronic map if they become unconscious, according to The Times
published here today.
</P>
<P>
BT is developing a range of devices to help the disabled and
elderly people become less house-bound. Panic buttons that alert
the police or a carer are already routinely used to help the frail
and disabled to live in their own homes, but BT researchers are
studying ways of extending the idea.
</P>
<P>
Don Golding, of BT's laboratories at Martlesham Heath, Suffolk,
said that phones could be set up to trigger an alarm. For example,
if someone was on an errand or an outing, a central controller
could ring at a preset time to check they were all right.
</P>
<P>
An alarm call might be made automatically if the person strayed
outside a predetermined area. The call center could then alert an
ambulance or a member of the family.
</P>
<P>
"The call center could bring up information about the person
such as medical needs or telephone number of their doctor,"
Golding said.
</P>
<P>
The call center could also be used as an advice point. Golding
said that a person in a wheelchair who, for example, got stuck on
a country walk, could dial the center which could put them in
touch with the nearest taxi firm to come to their aid.
</P>
<P>
BT is looking at using the cell-phone network for the
system. Signals from the phone to at least three cellular
transmitters would allow the network to pinpoint the phone's
location. 
</P>
</TEXT>
