<HEADLINE> HK's Hang Seng Bank Centralizes Back-Offices in New Tower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Hang Seng Bank, the second
largest locally-incorporated bank in Hong Kong, has relocated its
major back-office operations to the new Hang Seng Tower in East
Kowloon, to enhance the bank's operational and cost efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The bank has invested over 1.2 billion HK dollars (154 million
U.S. dollars) in the premises, including purchase, decoration and
equipment costs.
</P>
<P>
The premises, which comprise 10 stories of office space, were
bought for about 1.1 billion HK dollars (141 million U.S. dollars)
in August 1995 and marked the bank's largest property purchase.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,300 staff from the bank's Credit Card Center, Trade
Services Center, Direct Banking Center and Network Support Center
occupy the new offices.
</P>
<P>
"The total office space occupied by our various support
departments in this building has increased by more than 50 percent
against their former locations. The additional space will cater
for their expansion until the year 2000," Alexander S. K. Au,
vice-chairman and chief executive of the bank, told the opening
ceremony of the tower today.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1933, Hang Seng Bank employs a staff of over 8,000
in its 147 local branches, as well as branch and representative
offices on the mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
