<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Restates Support to ECOWAS Move on S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The efforts by west African
countries to solve the crisis in Sierra Leone got a boost Tuesday
when the United State reiterated its support to their measures
taken to reverse the May 25 coup in that country.
</P>
<P>
In a State Department statement, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said "we fully support ECOWAS' efforts to
restore President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah through mediation and the
use of sanctions."
</P>
<P>
"If negotiations do not succeed rapidly, we are deeply
concerned that force may be used instead," she said, quoted by
reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the remarks after a U.S. envoy was sent to
Sierra Leone to press for the return of the ousted legitimate
government.
</P>
<P>
The State Department statement said that Ambassador John
Hirsch will also consult with the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) on restoring democracy in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS leaders are to meet at a summit beginning this Thursday
in the Nigerian capital Abuja. The Sierra Leonean crisis is
expected to dominate the two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers and defence chiefs of the sub-region held
their respective meetings Tuesday in Abuja to discuss
recommendations and solutions for the coming summit.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Nigeria's head of state General Abacha, who is also
current chairman of ECOWAS, visited Cote d'Ivoire, Guinea, Mali
and Gambia, all ECOWAS member countries.
</P>
<P>
He is reported to be in these countries to express his
disposition toward military action to oust the military junta in
Sierra Leone that has announced to remain in power until 2001.
</P>
<P>
Many observers here believe that the sub-region might be
arriving at a diplomatic consensus for the seeming inevitability
of the use of force.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's meeting of army chiefs from ECOWAS member
countries, Nigeria's Chief of Defense Staff Major-General
Abdulsalam Abubakar admitted that "from all indications, peaceful
resolution through dialogue has failed."
</P>
<P>
He therefore stressed tightened sanctions and embargo as a
means to force the junta to step down.
</P>
<P>
He also commended the success of the sub-regional peacekeeping
force known as ECOMOG in Liberia, saying: "We can successfully
undertake collective action in our sub-region."
</P>
<P>
According to Abubakar, the coup in Sierra Leone is capable of
destabilizing the peace and harmony in the sub-region and
undermining the resolve of ECOWAS to guarantee a stable policy.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the crisis was not insurmountable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
