<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stock Market Under Selling Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Index (CI) of
the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange today slipped further on continued
selling, mostly by foreign funds, due to the weakening ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Heavy foreign selling was seen on most blue chip counters.
</P>
<P>
The CI fell 8.08 points to close at 847.92 today against
Tuesday's close of 856.00 points.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts said foreign investors were shying away as they
felt that the bearish sentiment which remained on the stock market
and the weakening ringgit were signs of economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
At the close today, the ringgit was at 2.8260/10 against the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Emas Index also lost 2.79 points to 245.42, the second
board index slipped 13.52 points to 434.31, while the Industrial
Index fell 2.12 points to 1,742.88.
</P>
<P>
Losers led gainers by 598 counters to 107 with 99 others traded
unchanged and 82 untraded.
</P>
<P>
Turnover for the day totaled 319.297 million shares worth 1.499
billion ringgit (about 530 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The main board volume increased to 280.781 million shares worth
1.165 billion ringgit (about 410 million U.S. dollars) from
254.018 million shares valued at 1.106 billion ringgit (about 390
million U.S. dollars) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Second board volume also rose to 38.516 million shares worth
333.197 million ringgit (about 118.99 million U.S. dollars) from
34.821 million shares valued at 325.707 million ringgit (about
116.32 million U.S. dollars) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Direct business transactions increased to 63.617 million shares
worth 448.083 million ringgit (about 160.02 million U.S. dollars)
from 31.175 million shares worth 246.190 million ringgit (about
87.92 million U.S. dollars) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts do not see the market recover in the short period as
foreign funds continue to look at the local stock market by the
performance of the ringgit and the trade data.
</P>
<P>
The July trade data to be released either tomorrow or the day
after are anticipated to see a deficit of about 800 million
ringgit (about 285.71 million U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
