<HEADLINE> Foreign Residents Satisfied with Public Order in Tianjin City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey of foreign
residents in Tianjin, a port city in north China, showed that 94
percent of the respondents are satisfied with the city's public
order.
</P>
<P>
The figure has increased by 4.7 percentage points, compared
with a similar survey conducted by the local police three years
ago. And nearly 90 percent of the foreign residents said they feel
safe in the city, an increase of 10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The survey questioned more than 1,690 foreigners from 57
countries and regions, including the United States, Japan and
Singapore. The foreigners surveyed included enterpreneurs,
technical personnel, teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
The city, with a population of nearly 10 million, has become
famous for its low crime rate in the last four years, which has
become a main attraction to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
An American teacher working at Tianjin Teacher's University had
suggested in the survey that an English interpreter be hired to
receive emergency calls in the police station. To his surprise,
the police immediately accepted his advice.
</P>
<P>
"I hadn't expected they would pay attention to my idea. Their
ability to deal well with the public is a sign of the city's good
public order," the teacher said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
