<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Ringgit Dips Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's ringgit dipped
further to breach the 2.8200 mark in late trading today.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit, which opened at 2.7945/95 against the U.S. dollar
this morning, dipped to 2.8070/90 at around 3:40 p.m. after
hovering at between 2.7940 and 2.8050 earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
It then drifted further to 2.8260/10 at the close, a plunge of
almost 380 points against Tuesday's close of 2.7880/10.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit like the Thai baht and Indonesian rupiah has been
under a lot of pressure of late. The local unit is being pressured
by talks that U.S. funds were accumulating long dollar/ringgit
positions.
</P>
<P>
The weakening in the stock market has also fueled the selling
of the ringgit as offshore players liquidated their stocks and
then sold ringgit and bought U.S. dollars to repatriate their
funds.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the stock market's barometer, the Composite Index,
hit a new 31-month low when it touched the 871.75 level. It was
870.75 on January 25, 1995.
</P>
<P>
"There is a possibility that the ringgit may touch the 3.00
level to the U.S. dollar," a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Another dealer said ringgit speculation was not a new problem
to the local financial market as between 1993 and 1994 there was a
massive inflow of short-term speculative funds into the system.
</P>
<P>
"The rise and fall of a currency is normal, and the country's
currency is still considered 'stable'," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, market observers said the ringgit's downslide was
still prevailing and the local unit may continue to be weak in the
coming weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
