<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Cracks Down On Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region in south China solved 245 smuggling cases involving
200 million yuan between January and June this year.
</P>
<P>
Customs officials and police also seized 94,000 grams of heroin
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has long coastal lines and borders Vietnam and
Myanmar. The complex geographic features make the region a good
passageway for smugglers.
</P>
<P>
The smuggled goods included automobiles and automobile parts,
cigarettes, drugs, oil products and weapons. During the first half
of this year, for example, 168 cars were confiscated by police and
customs officials.
</P>
<P>
The region has in recent years stepped up its crackdown on
illegal trafficking by tightening supervision on markets and ports
that are open to border trade. Checks on cargo ships on the sea
waters have also been intensified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
