<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Allows Political Campaigns Through Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The House of Representatives has
approved on third and final reading a bill which allows the use of
mass media for political campaigns, the Philippines News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The existing law prohibits all candidates, without exception,
from using mass media for political campaigns and other purposes,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, House Speaker Jose de Venecia said the 1992 elections
showed that the ban on media advertisement diminished the chances
of newcomers to get elected, thus, instead of leveling the playing
field, the ban actually favored candidates already known to the
public.
</P>
<P>
The bill, approved Tuesday night, recommends that political
parties and candidates be allowed to buy air time and print space
directly from duly registered mass media such as newspapers,
magazines, radio and television.
</P>
<P>
The country would have its presidential election in May next
year and de Venecia is one of the presidential aspirants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts on Universal Declaration of Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese human rights expert Fan
Guoxiang said here today the importance of human rights has
acquired a world-wide acknowledgment since the adoption of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights on December 10, 1948.
</P>
<P>
Fan made the remarks at the 49th session of the Sub-Commission
on Prevention of Discrimination and Protection of Minorities under
the United Nations Human Rights Committee, scheduled for August
4-29.
</P>
<P>
"In my view, the Universal Declaration of Human Rights is an
important historical document," Fan said, "At the same time, it
has its historical limitations. Nearly half a century has elapsed,
full of earth-shaking events of a broad spectrum."
</P>
<P>
Since the adoption of the declaration, the membership of the
United Nations has been more than tripled. "It is only natural
that newly independent developing countries have their interests
and concerns to look after", Fan said.
</P>
<P>
The declaration has been continuously enriched with the passage
of time, with some 80 declarations, conventions, convenants,
principles, rules, safeguards, codes of conduct, guidelines,
protocols, and statutes added so far.
</P>
<P>
"Historical development in the world will inevitably offer new
basis to build up fresh ideas on human rights, which, in return,
will contribute to a better and deeper public awareness of the
rights and interests of the people so that further social progress
may be achieved," Fan said, adding that human rights, "both
factual and conceptual, cannot remain static." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
