<HEADLINE> Non-Traditional Products Boost Uganda's Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The total export value of
Uganda increased from 538 millions U.S. Dollars in 1986/1987
financial year to 750 millions U.S. Dollars in 1996/1997
financial year due to the growth of non-traditional products, The
Monitor, reported today.
</P>
<P>
In its report, "Focus on Uganda's Exports 1986-1996", the
Uganda export promotion board said non-traditional exports rose
from two percent of the total value in 1986/1987 financial year
to 26 percent in 1996/1997 financial year while traditional
exports decreased from 98 percent to 73 percent in the same
period.
</P>
<P>
Robert Rutagi, the executive director of the Uganda Export
Promotion Board, told the paper in an exclusive interview that
high value crops brought maximum returns and added value to
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Non-traditional export products in Uganda include fish,
flowers and grains.
</P>
<P>
Fish and fish products export earning of Uganda increased by
222 percent from 0.11 million U.S. Dollars in 1986/1987 financial
year to 24.5 millions U.S. Dollars in 1996/1997 financial year
while the value of flowers grew from zero in 1993 to 3.4 millions
U.S. Dollars in 1996/1997 financial year.
</P>
<P>
Traditional export products of Uganda include coffee, cotton,
tobacco and tea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
