<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Substances Used in Tobacco Industry Depleting Ozone Layer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Two chemical substances used in
the cultivation and processing of tobacco can cause depletion of
the ozone layer, according to an American scholar speaking at the
ongoing 10th World Conference on Tobacco or Health.
</P>
<P>
Methyl bromide, a potent pesticide which is widely used in the
tobacco cultivation both for soil pre-treatment and fumigation, is
causing an estimated 10 percent of the global ozone depletion each
year, said Fran du Melle, deputy managing director of the American
Lung Cancer Association.
</P>
<P>
"The odorless, colorless, tasteless gas is also known to be
toxic to the central nervous system, the lungs and kidneys, and is
a potential human carcinogen" Melle said.
</P>
<P>
Chloroflourocarbons, used in the processing of tobacco, also
are responsible for eroding the ozone layer, she said.
</P>
<P>
Since the ozone shields the earth from the sun's damaging
ultraviolet rays, its disappearance may result in increased risk
of skin cancer and cataracts as well as immune system suppression,
she explained. It may also lead to economic loss for agriculture,
fisheries, forests and tourism, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Vienna Convention and its Montreal Protocol on Substances
that Deplete the Ozone Layer were signed in 1987 to protect the
ozone, she said.
</P>
<P>
According to the protocol, developed countries were required to
freeze their production and consumption of methyl bromide in 1995
at a base level, and completely stop using the substance by 2010;
while developing countries are to freeze production and use at low
levels in 2002.
</P>
<P>
"The tobacco industry is rapidly shifting from the outdoor
seedbed method, which requires fumigating the soil, to on-farm
greenhouses," Melle said. In the United States, she added, the
shift is expected to affect 90 percent of the tobacco production
by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China, Brazil, Thailand, Zimbabwe and other
developing countries are also experimenting with alternatives to
methyl bromide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
