<HEADLINE> Nigeria: 100 Feared Dead in Boat Mishap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- About 100 people, mainly women
and children, were feared dead when two boats collided along the
</P>
<P>
About 80 survivors were reported to have been rescued by
Tuesday morning, while no corpses had been found as of Tuesday
evening, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The large wooden boats have a capacity of 80 passengers each
but were said to be carrying about 120 passengers apiece.
</P>
<P>
A survivor attributed the accident of Monday night to bad
weather, saying there was heavy downpour which impaired
visibility and made it difficult for the drivers to manipulate
the boats which were filled beyond capacity.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the number of people whose whereabouts were yet to
be ascertained, property worth millions of naira was lost.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred 48 hours after a similar one involving a
speed boat claiming two lives on the Bonny River in Port
Harcourt, the oil producing base of the country.
</P>
<P>
The speed boat carrying about 18 passengers ran under water
after suffering a serious wave-battering from a passing powerful
oil company barge.
</P>
<P>
On July 23, about 10 persons drowned in another boat mishap
when the boat in which they were travelling capsized mid-sea.
</P>
<P>
pAAccording to reports, traffic has been on the rise in the
area as more people move from Port Harcourt to Bonny and Bayelsa
state in search of work and other economic activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
