<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Free of Anti-Personnel Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Belgium has become a country
free of anti-personnel mines after it transported Tuesday its last
batch of such military devices for destruction in neighboring
Germany.
</P>
<P>
A train carrying of 115,480 anti-personnel mines left Bertrix
late Tuesday and arrived overnight at Pinnow in Germany, where the
mines will be destroyed through incineration.
</P>
<P>
Belgium has chosen Germany for the destruction of
anti-personnel mines because it is less expensive there. Domestic
incinerators had demanded some 40 Belgian francs for destroying a
single mine.
</P>
<P>
Belgium is the first country in the world to have made a law in
1995 banning the production, exportation and utilization of
anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
In December 1996, Belgium destroyed a total of 313,472
anti-personnel mines in Germany.
</P>
<P>
So far, all European Union member states, except Greece and
Finland, have banned anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that about 100 million
anti-personnel mines have been laid out throughout the world since
World War II, which combine to claim an annual casualties of some
20,000 people, mostly innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
Most of the live anti-personnel mines still can be found in
former conflict-stricken regions such as Cambodia,
Bosnia-Herzegovina and Somalia and along common borders of former
Cold War foes like Finland and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
