<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
limped to a slightly higher close with a strong performance by
media giant News Corp offsetting a weaker U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
Scott Enns, a broker for Henderson Carlton Jones, said Rupert
Murdoch's News Corp had helped to push the market up during the
day despite generally weak trading.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 0.2 points up at 2,626.5. It
traded in a range of 2,631.8 and 2,621.6.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed 4.5 points higher at 4,224.3,
underpinned by rises of 2.75 percent by News Corp, 4.72 percent by
its preferred shares and 4.01 percent by construction company
Leighton Holdings.
</P>
<P>
News Corp's ordinary shares closed 16 cents higher at 5.98
Australian dollars on turnover of 3.4 million shares and its
preferred shares added 23 cents to 5.10 Australian dollars on
turnover of 3.3 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Media giant John Fairfax climbed two cents to 3.27 Australian
dollars and Kerry Packer's Publishing and Broadcasting lost one
cent to 8.12 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Shares in construction concern Leighton Holdings jumped 26
cents to 6.75 Australian dollars, after the company nearly
doubling its annual net profit results last week to 97.75 million
US dollars from 51.94 million US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
And shares in automotive supplier GUD Holdings jumped eight
cents to 4.50 Australian dollars after posting a solid 35 percent
rise in annual after-tax earnings to 10.61 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Amongst the banks, National Australia Bank shed six to 18.98
Australian dollars on turnover of 2.2 million shares, ANZ rose
eight to 10.08 Australian dollars, CBA inched six up to 15.27
Australian dollars with 3.8 million shares turned over and Westpac
dropped two to 8.03 Australian dollars.
</P>
