<HEADLINE> Law Association for Asia-Pacific Meets in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 lawyers, judges
and justices in the Asia-Pacific region gathered here today to
discuss challenges facing the judiciary sector in a changing Asia.
</P>
<P>
They are attending the five-day 15th biennial conference of the
Law Association for Asia and the Pacific (Lawasia) which will end
August 31.
</P>
<P>
The participants will discuss rules on foreign investment,
energy insecurity, impact of laws on environment and corruption,
and other issues.
</P>
<P>
The delegates include about 20 chief justices and over 1,000
lawyers, judges and appellate court justices from 32 members of
Lawasia, including China, Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos delivered a speech at the opening
ceremony, calling for lawyers and lawmakers in the region to
cooperate closely to protect common people and their nations from
such problems as drug-trafficking and assaults on national
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the chief justices also met for the 7th Conference
of Chief Justices of Asia and the Pacific to discuss the
independence of the judiciary, judicial corruption and current
challenges in the management of lower courts.  
