<HEADLINE> Philippine President Defends Changes to Charter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos said today
that amending the constitution will make the country's political
system more responsive to the challenges and opportunities the
incoming century will bring.
</P>
<P>
It was the third time this week that Ramos defended the charter
change campaigns seeking to extend the term of elective officials
including the president.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines must re-examine its constitution thoroughly to
improve the country's capacity to promote the interests of the
national community, Ramos told the opening of the Biennial
Conference of the Law Association of Asia and the Pacific in
Manila.
</P>
<P>
"While I have stated time and again my stand on this issue --
that I do not seek a second term for myself -- I nevertheless
recognize and respect the people's right to petition for
constitutional change," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was also the right of congressmen to decide what is best for
the country's future by ways of enlightened laws and even
amendments to the Constitution, he said, referring to the move by
Congress to convene itself into a constitutional assembly to
discuss Charter changes.
</P>
<P>
Opposition senators and congressmen have rejected the move to
amend the Charter at this time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
