<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mao Zedong's Hometown to Present New Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Changsha, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Hunan Province, the hometown of
the late Chairman Mao Zedong, is to emerge as an economic power in
central China due to a strengthened opening-up policy on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, the province has reported a
12 percent increase in its gross domestic product -- the value of
goods and services produced -- over the corresponding period last
year, which is 2.6 percentage points higher than the national
average.
</P>
<P>
Aimed at an economic take-off, Hunan has no choice but to adopt
a more deepened opening-up policy, said Wang Maolin, secretary of
the Hunan Provincial Committee of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
The province, a renowned revolutionary base for Mao during the
1930s, lagged behind its coastal counterparts during the early
years of China's reform and opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, designated as Hunan's "year of improvement in
investment environment," the province drew foreign investment
equaling half the total volume in the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
Though a landlocked province, Hunan borders on two of the most
vibrant regions in the country, the Yangtze River Economic
Belt to the east and the South-China Economic Belt to the south.
</P>
<P>
"We'll make the best use of this geographical location," Wang
said.
</P>
<P>
He said a city belt along the Beijing-Guangzhou Rail Artery,
with capital city Changsha at the core, will be built into an
economic corridor where a concentration of high-tech industries,
export-oriented enterprises and high-profit trading companies will
gather.
</P>
<P>
The corridor has attracted 70 percent of all foreign capital
flowing into the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
