<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Tourist Arrivals Up Sharply in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The number of foreign tourists
traveling to northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
has been increasing sharply in recent months, local officials
announced today.
</P>
<P>
Some 14,000 foreigners arrived in Xinjiang in July, 30 percent
more than in the previous month, Zhang Jie, an accountant with the
regional Tourism Bureau, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The figure is estimated to jump to 21,000 this month, up 10
percent from last August, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang, rich in both natural and cultural resources targeting
tourists, has witnessed a continuous rise in foreign visitors
since mid-spring.
</P>
<P>
In May and June, the region received 22,000 foreign tourists,
equaling to the total number from the January-April period. Local
officials expected that the tourism industry will maintain the
momentum in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
After a five-day stay in Xinjiang last week, Mr. Pascal, an
architect from Switzerland, described Xinjiang as "extremely
attractive."
</P>
<P>
"There are unique scenic spots here. Local people seem to live
a good life," Pascal said.
</P>
<P>
Folke Von Knbloch, general manager of the Central Asia Tourism
Corporation based in Alma-Ata, who recently completed a month-long
business trip in the region, remarked that Xinjiang has great
potential for tourism and investment.
</P>
<P>
He said he plans to spend 100,000 U.S. dollars on building a
ski course in Yili Prefecture in West Xinjiang. "Tourists from
southeast Asian countries will definitely like it," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
