<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Rationing Imminent in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is expected to
experience another power rationing this year due to declining
water level at the giant Mtera hydroelectric power plant.
</P>
<P>
The warning was made by Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye while
adjourning the current National Assembly budget session in Dodoma
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye in his speech directed accounting officers in
government departments to ensure that power was used
economically, saying that effective this fiscal year they must
settle power bills from their budgets.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the government would no longer shoulder the
burden of serving electricity and water bills of the public
offices.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed his disappointment with some
government offices which left their lights on even when the
offices were closed or during weekends or public holidays.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye said that to avert the power problem, various
alternative sources of power would be surveyed and established to
ensure factories produce at their installed capacities and the
state earn its much needed revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
