<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda, Congo (K), Rwanda Studying Road Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A study to link Uganda, Rwanda
and Congo (k) by road, rail and water was launched here Tuesday
after two days of talks by experts from the three countries,
reported the local daily, The New Vision, today.
</P>
<P>
The study will cost 300,000 U.S. Dollars to be contributed by
the members, the paper said, adding that a joint technical task
group to carry out the study was ready.
</P>
<P>
The study follows a decision by the presidents of the three
countries who met recently in Kinshasa, to link their countries
to facilitate trade and increase cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On the railway link, according to Ugandan Minister of Works,
Transport and Communications, John Nasasira, the task group is to
study the Kasese-Goma-Kigali and the Kasese-Kisangani-Pakwach
links. Preliminary studies have shown that the Kampala-Kasese
route was feasible with a capacity of moving cargo to the tune of
800,000 tons at a time.
</P>
<P>
This is equivalent to the capacity at which Uganda's cargo
moves through Mombasa and Dar Es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
On road network, the study will include Arua-Aru-Mahagi and
Nebbi- Goli-Mahagi-Bunia and Kisangani while another will be
Kases-Mpondwe-Beni-Mambasa.
</P>
<P>
On water transport, the technical group will study how to link
the three countries through lakes.
</P>
<P>
The telephone network to link the members is yet to be
studied.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ministers of communications from the three
countries will soon lead a delegation to the European Union to
solicit for funding for the project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
