<HEADLINE> Belgian Defense Minister Approves Airshow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Defense Minister
Jean-Paul Poncelet has approved an airshow scheduled for early
next month at Florenne.
</P>
<P>
Poncelet approved the acrobatic flights after receiving and
reviewing safety and security reports from show organizers, local
television RTBF reported today.
</P>
<P>
The airshow will be held on September 6-7, the first after a
crash at the July 26 airshow at Ostend, killing 10 people and
injuring 55 others.
</P>
<P>
All acrobatic flights had been under an investigation after the
crash, results of which attributed the crash at the Belgian
seaside resort to errors committed by the pilot of the Falcon
XT300 biplane.
</P>
<P>
After analyzing video recordings of the fatal flight and the
debris of the crashed plane, aviation experts and designers and
manufacturers of the German-made acrobatics-oriented plane
concluded that the pilot, Captain Amr Hani Bilal of the Jordanian
Royal Falcon Squadron, was flying directly overhead the spectators
before the plane spun out of control and crashed onto a tent at
the edge of the spectator area.
</P>
<P>
Planes are not allowed to fly directly overhead the spectators
at airshows and the display must be interrupted when a plane
crosses the display line, usually the runway on the airfield.
</P>
<P>
The Ostend airshow has been held five times and the July 26
crash was the first fatal accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
