<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Develops World's First Anti-Hacking Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Information Security
Agency (KISA) has developed two anti-hacking software products,
possibly the first hacker-tracing program in the world.
</P>
<P>
Online SecuDr is a program designed to diagnose a computer
system's vulnerability to hackers, while SecuLog frustrates
attempts to erase or alter traces of illegal penetration, Goh
Seung-cheol, a senior KISA researcher, was quoted by a local
newspaper today as saying.
</P>
<P>
Using Online SecuDr, KISA has started its free diagnosis
service, which is available on request. System managers who want
to check their systems can request the service by accessing the
agency's Internet home page (http://www.kisa.or.kr) and punching
in the names of the host computer, its address and type of
operating system.
</P>
<P>
With the information, Online SecuDr would automatically check
the system, determine its weaknesses and send a diagnosis to the
system managers via e-mail, Goh said, adding that the service
"will be very useful in preventing hacking".
</P>
<P>
He said SecuLog, a program to trace hackers, would
automatically retrieves log files which hackers abolish or alter
to eliminate any trace of their infiltration.
</P>
<P>
A log file records all attempts to access a computer
system. System managers usually hide about 200 hard copies of the
log file in their own computers, making it difficult for hackers
to destroy it completely.
</P>
<P>
"It usually takes time for hackers to delete all of the 200
copies hidden in the computers of system managers. SecuLog races
against the hackers to retrieve the log file. If hackers fail to
destroy all of the 200 copies before SecuLog retrieves any of
them, they lose and leave behind evidence of their break-in," Goh
said.
</P>
<P>
He said since SecuLog is the first hacker-tracing program in
the world, they are planning to apply for domestic and
international patents and also to transfer the technology to a
private software developer for its commercialization.
</P>
<P>
Till a commercial product comes out, the agency plans to
provide the program to those who want it, which is available in
Korean- and English-language versions.
</P>
<P>
Goh added that his team would begin upgrading the program as
hackers are expected to develop ways around it in about two
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agassi Returns to Win in U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Open champion Andre
Agassi returned to win over his compatriot Steve Campbell 6-1,
6-1, 4-6, 6-3 on Tuesday night in the first round of the U.S. Open
tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, former No.1 in the world, played as the old one to go
through half of the match when he broke six times. Feeling the
pressure of Agassi's unleashed backhand, 130th-ranked Campbell
held his serve just once before he pull back one set when Agassi's
form wavered slightly.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, losing semifinalist of last year's U.S. Open, soon
recuperated and the rout continued to its inevitable conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Agassi has lost seven of ten tournaments this year. Tuesday's
win was a good starter when he returned to the Grand Slam with his
ever-lowest rank as 63rd in the world.
</P>
<P>
In other matches on Tuesday, Michael Chang, second seed and
last year's runner-up, and third-seeded Russian Yevgeny Kafelnikov
blasted their opponents with straight wins.
</P>
<P>
Ninth seed French Open champion Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil
breezed over American qualifier Geoff Grant 6-4, 3-6, 6-7, 6-2,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
Eighth-seeded Australian Open runner-up Carolos Moya of Spain
slumped into a humiliating defeat against 64th-ranked Guillaume
Raoux of France. His compatriot 16th seed Albert Costa failed to
have his name on the second-round list too in a clash with another
Frenchman Arnaud Boetsch, ranked 31st.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Alex Corretja of Spain trounced Marc Rosset of
Switzerland 4-6, 6-3, 6-2, 6-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
