<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serb Republic Adopts Resolution Against Plavsic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- No decisions made by Bosnian
Serb President Biljana Plavsic on the change of military and civil
personnel will be approved by the Parliament, the Republic of
Srpska declared today in Pale.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament of the Republic of Srpska held a meeting today
in Pale and passed a resolution on the current crisis facing the
republic, the Yugoslav Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament will neither discuss nor accept any of the
decisions made by Plavsic bypassing the constitution and laws,
the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the constitutional court of the republic declared
unconstitutional Plavsic's decision to dissolve the Parliament,
the political and security situation in the republic has rapidly
deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
It is likely to lead to a split in the people from the organs
of power, and a split in the nation, the resolution pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also accused multinational Stablization Force
(SFOR), the International Police Task Force (IPTF) and the
Organization for the Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) of
changing their authorizations.
</P>
<P>
The three forces, the resolution noted, threw weight behind one
of the conflicting sides, which could make the Republic of Srpska
a protected nation subject to military occupation.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament required the government and all its institutions
to most firmly defend the independence of the Bosnian Serb
Republic, its constitutional order and organs of power.
</P>
<P>
The government, the Interior Ministry and security institutions
should work out an action plan within 24 hours to defend the
constitutional order and organs of power, demanded the resolution.
</P>
<P>
With the conflicts inside the leading body of the republic
coming into the open, the conflicts and struggles between Plavsic
and the Parliament as well as the government which was on the side
of the Parliament became increasingly intense.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts and opposition within the leading body have
generated a crisis of emerging two political powers in the
Republic of Srpska. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
