<HEADLINE> China Steps up Reforms in Tourism Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- China will open up its tourism
sector in the next few years to make it better fit the reforms in
the socialist market economic framework, says He Guangwei,
chairman of the China National Tourism Administration.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that the country's tourism industry will make
some improvements based on the work of the past several years, and
that the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) should have a far-reaching impact on the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
The tourism industry has made some progress and has become one
of the fastest-growing sectors of the national economy in recent
years. In 1996, China ranked fifth in the world in the number of
overseas tourists and ninth in foreign exchange earnings from
tourism.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, the number of overseas tourists annually to China is
expected to reach about 71 million and earnings, about 43 billion
US dollars. There will be an estimated 2.5 billion Chinese also
traveling in the country, who will bring an additional one
trillion yuan (126.5 billion US dollars) in earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps up Reform in Tourism Industry (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"To attain that ambitious goal, we must take the necessary
steps in introducing a modern enterprise system to the tourist
industry by the end of this century", He observed.
</P>
<P>
Existing large tourism enterprises will be transformed into
more powerful conglomerates by issuing shares, and medium-sized
enterprises will be encouraged to become corporations.
</P>
<P>
Small enterprises will be helped through reorganization,
mergers, acquisitions, and share issue.
</P>
<P>
While reforms are being pushed forward, measures will also be
taken to open-up the tourism sector still wider, He noted,
explaining, "We continue to welcome and encourage overseas
business people to invest in hotels, scenic spots, tourism product
development and transportation."
</P>
<P>
"We also welcome overseas travel agencies with a good
reputation to set up joint venture travel agencies in national
holiday resorts."
</P>
