<HEADLINE> China Steps up Reform in Tourism Industry (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1996, self-paid tourists on package tours organized by
travel agencies made up 32.4 percent of the Chinese travelling
overseas, as opposed to fewer than 20 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there were 636 million Chinese traveling in the
country, and spending 163.8 billion yuan (19.734 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said he believes progress in the tourist industry is mainly
attributable to the strong support from the Chinese government,
which in 1992 listed it as one of the focuses of the service
sector for accelerated development.
</P>
<P>
It was at this time that tourism was, for the first time,
considered an industry instead of part of foreign affairs as it
had been previously.
</P>
<P>
The status of tourism was further improved when, at the Fifth
Plenary Session of the 14th CPC Central Committee held in 1995,
tourism was put in first place in the service sector for "vigorous
development".
</P>
<P>
"The attention of the central government has aroused the
enthusiasm of local governments in developing tourism," He said.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 of China's 31 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities directly under the central government have
designated tourism as a pillar industry. 
</P>
