<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Farmer Finds Old Olympic Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 27 (Xinhua) -- An Olympic medal dating back sixty
years that was discovered by a farmer in Hubei province in central
China is believed by experts to be a bronze medal for the 1936
winter Olympic games at Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany.
</P>
<P>
The farmer found the medal two years ago when his house was
being torn down for renovation. He took it for an ordinary old
coin and gave it to his child to play with.
</P>
<P>
Last summer, when he was watching the Olympic Games in Atlanta
on TV, he recognized the design on his coin as the same design on
the screen, the Olympic logo.
</P>
<P>
So, he sent the medal to Beijing, where a close examination by
experts showed that the bronze medal had the Olympic logo in the
middle and the date and place of the games engraved around it. The
reverse side has the image of skis, ski boots and a carriage.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the bronze medal could hardly have belonged to any
Chinese person because China did not take part in those games. But
because Jingshan county, where the farmer lives, is near the
Hankou-Yichang highway, where the Japanese troops had a strong
presence during the War of Resistance Against Japanese Aggression
(1937-1945), it might have belonged to a Japanese soldier or
officer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
