<HEADLINE> Ho Chi Minh Cave Discovered In Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- A cave in southwest China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has been identified as a hide-out
of Ho Chi Minh, the former leader of the Vietnamese Communist
Party, in the 1940's.
</P>
<P>
The cave was called "yanlin" in the Zhuang language, meaning a
cave with ventilation. It is 60 m long and has a small entrance
sheltered by thick plants.
</P>
<P>
It was being used as a place to make spirits by a local man,
Huang Caihan, in 1942 when a friend introduced Ho Chi Minh who
needed a place to live.
</P>
<P>
Huang, who is now 84, says that Ho often helped him make fire
and taste the alcohol and that they called each other brother.
</P>
<P>
According to Huang, Vietnamese Communist Party members came to
the cave frequently and left many poems there. One poem written by
Ho can still be seen on the ceiling of the cave.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
