<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Practice New Regulations on Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar will practice new
regulations on remittance abroad of foreign exchange, according to
today's official paper The New Light of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Myanmar Minister for Finance and Revenue Win
Tin as saying that if the Foreign Exchange Certificate (FEC),
which is equivalent to the U.S. dollar in value in Myanmar and
legally circulated on the market, is purchased with Myanmar
currency kyat and deposited in the account of the state-run
foreign exchange bank, payment for imports and remittance abroad
will be permitted up to only 50,000 U.S. dollars per month.
</P>
<P>
If the FEC is deposited in the bank through sale of imports and
local goods, payment for imports, remittance abroad and repayment
for loan and interest will also be permitted up to the same amount
per month, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
If foreign exchange is received from export, the new
regulations have no such limit to the payment and will be handled
in accordance with the prevailing method.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Luxembourg PM Visits Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Slovakia should not be excluded
from the European Union (EU) forever, says visiting Luxembourg
Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker.
</P>
<P>
Juncker, also president of EU, made this remark in a speech in
Prague on Monday.
</P>
<P>
After several rounds of negotiations in Strasbourg, the EU
decided on July 16 that among the 11 countries which are applying
for EU membership, the Czech Republic and five other nations
were expected to be the first candidates to join in talks for
membership. Slovakia was excluded from the talks.
</P>
<P>
Juncker met Czech President Vaclav Havel, Prime Minister Vaclav
Klaus and Minister of Foreign Affairs Josef Zieleniec. During
their talks, the two sides exchanged views on the way to prepare
the Czech Republic for EU membership. Juncker promised that
Luxembourg would make all efforts to get the negotiations for EU
membership started no later than early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Juncker arrived in Prague on August 24 for a three-day
visit. He and his entourage left for Slovakia today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
