<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Drug Peddlers Arrested in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Two Pakistani passport holders
have been arrested in Kathmandu for drug trafficking, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Khalik and Nashrullah, allegedly notorious drug peddlers,
were caught red-handed Monday when they were trying to sell in a
shop a coat containing heroin worth 25,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Altogether four such coats were recovered from the duo with 870
grams of white heroin worth 16 million rupees (about 280,000
dollars), the reports quoted an anti-drug official as saying.
</P>
<P>
These drugs could fetch 440,000 dollars in the market of the
United States, the official added.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary inquiries, the two revealed that their
coats were prepared in Pakistan by another party and that they
were here just to sell them.
</P>
<P>
The duo is believed to be important members of a large drug
racket operating in the region, which has been using Pakistan as
conduit to supply Afghan drugs to the West, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Their passports show that they have traveled to Nepal thrice
between March and May this year.
</P>
<P>
This time the police managed to net in the duo after being
tipped off by international agencies, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
