<HEADLINE> India to Increase Outlay for Small Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- India is planning to increase
its outlay for the country's small scale industries (SSI) in the
Ninth Five-Year Plan (1998-2002) in a bid to enhance its
development.
</P>
<P>
The Industry Ministry has proposed to spend 42,960 million
rupees (1,210.14 million U.S. dollars) during the period against
an outlay of 28,621.4 million rupees (817.75 million dollars) in
the Eighth Five-Year Plan period, the ministry sources said here
today.
</P>
<P>
SSI units, badly hit by low quality technology, are expected to
get 9,550 million rupees (269.01 million dollars) as central
assistance during the plan period for upgrading and modernization.
</P>
<P>
The Industry Ministry plans to pump in another 3,750 million
rupees (105.63 million dollars) for providing training and
developing human resources. The ministry has proposed to set up 60
leading skill and craft training centers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
SSI units have played an important role in India's economic
development. Exports from SSI sectors, for instance, account for
45 percent of the country's total exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
