<HEADLINE> Donating Blood Helps Reduce Risk of Heart Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Donating blood can help
reduce the risk of heart attacks and strokes in non-smoking men,
an American medical magazine reported.
</P>
<P>
After a three-year study of about 4,000 people, American
researchers found that the men who had never given blood were
almost twice as likely to have had a heart attack, stroke or
angina as those who had donated blood in the previous three years,
the journal Heart said.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of non-blood donors catching certain
cardiovascular diseases was also three times higher than donors,
the report by a Kansas University research team said.
</P>
<P>
"Depletion of iron through blood donation may reduce coronary
heart disease among donors," said David Meyers, head of the team.
</P>
<P>
Iron can help increase the production of fat-like substances in
the human body, which could narrow the artery walls and produce
potentially fatal clots, he said.
</P>
<P>
Women are less likely to suffer from heart disease because of
iron loss during their menstruation, the journal said.
</P>
<P>
However, the study shows that for men who smoked and women,
donating blood could not provide better protection against heart
disease. There was also no more benefit reported from donating
blood more than once every three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
