<HEADLINE> India Bans Four Companies from Exporting Seafood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 27 (Xinhua) -- India's Commerce Ministry has
suspended four companies from further exporting seafood, the
ministry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The action is seen here as damage-control exercises of the
Indian government in the wake of the proposed European Union (EU)
hygiene-related ban on the import of seafood from India recently.
</P>
<P>
An inspection team of the Commerce Ministry has been sent to
the coastal city, Cochin, in southern India, to ensure that
exporting units of seafood adhere to the stipulated hygiene norms.
</P>
<P>
The team will also identify the units that will continue to be
eligible to export their products.
</P>
<P>
India's 10 shipments of seafood worth about 36,000 U.S. dollars
had already been rejected between January and July this year by
European countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU had recommended a total ban for an unlimited period
after its team had visited and inspected the conditions of
exporting units in India. The team had found the conditions on
seafood farms very poor and had stipulated that these farms meet
international standards if they were to export their products to
EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU suspended the ban temporarily following repeated
requests from the Indian government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
