<HEADLINE> ASEAN Fund Hit By Currency Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The current currency crisis
across Southeast Asia is hitting a plan by the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) to enlarge its financial reserves
fund, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The crisis is discouraging ASEAN members from contributing to
the fund as each of them has incurred huge foreign debts during
their efforts to defend their own currencies, the Nation newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that five major ASEAN members had agreed at a
conference of East Asian and Pacific central banks in late July to
extend the ASEAN Reserves Fund by renewing a dormant 200 million
U.S. dollar swap agreement for one year beginning on August 5.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement concluded by Singapore, Indonesia,
Malaysia, Thailand and the Philippines, an ASEAN member country in
need of liquidity can exchange its local currency for U.S. dollars
provided by other members as a short-term means to improve their
balance of payment.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts praised the ASEAN move to increase the fund to
defend the currencies in the region, but doubted the plan will be
realized under the current circumstances as every country in the
region is eager for funds to survive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
