<HEADLINE> More Overseas Investment For East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 27 (Xinhua) -- China's Fujian province, a
pioneer in China's opening-up drive, will improve its investment
environment and services for overseas investors to attract more
overseas funds for its economic growth, according to Governor He
Guoqiang.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, Fujian had approved 21,700 overseas-funded
enterprises with a total of 46.96 billion dollars worth of capital.
</P>
<P>
The influx of funds, which now account for 40 percent of the
province's fixed assets investment, have become a powerful force
in the local economy, whose GDP topped 260.6 billion yuan in 1996,
the governor said. Fujian now leads the country in per-capita GDP.
</P>
<P>
However, a lack of services, which are important to the area's
investment growth, has been a source of complaints among overseas
business people and has in part contributed to a slump in overseas
investment in Fujian.
</P>
<P>
Fujian used 2.23 billion US dollars in overseas investment in
the first half of the year, up three percent from the same period
last year. But contractual investment fell 60 percent during that
period to a mere 1.59 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Fujian will attach importance to improving its infrastructure,
the governor said, and at the same time will make a point of
simplifying approval procedures and correcting such past practices
as excessive fees, while providing legal protection for overseas
investors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
