<HEADLINE> Drought in Indonesia Worsens Haze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The current drought in Indonesia
is expected to reach its climax in September as the water
shortage, haze, and drought-related health problems are likely to
worsen.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the drought, which has lasted for more than
three months, is part of the El Nino phenomenon, State Minister
for Environment Sarwono Kusumatmaja said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The latest data from the Environment Office indicated that
large-scale haze problems caused by fires are still affecting
Indonesia's Kalimantan, Riau, Jambi and South Sumatra provinces.
Around 16,000 hectares of forest areas have been burnt for
plantation in the country this year, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The haze has wrought havoc with flight schedules in the areas
and also neighboring Serawak and East Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and Malaysia have held talks to discuss the haze
problems while Singapore has sent a daily report on the latest
"hot spots" in Indonesia, Kusumatmaja said.
</P>
<P>
The most violent El Nino episode in 1982-83 was responsible for
almost 2,000 deaths and 13 billion U.S. dollars in damages as
droughts, fires, floods and hurricanes swept cross the global from
Tahiti to India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
