<HEADLINE> Tianjin's Living Conditions Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, August 27 (Xinhua) -- North China's port city of
Tianjin has built 20 million sq.m. of residential housing in the
past several years, improving living conditions for more than
400,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
Per capita living space in the city proper is twice what it was
a decade ago. Tianjin has raised 7.1 billion yuan for residential
housing construction since 1987 when it started reforming the old
practice of distributing government-subsidized apartments as a
form of welfare.
</P>
<P>
The city has also encouraged 80 housing co-operatives in
suburban towns and county seats and among workers with moderately
low incomes in the city.
</P>
<P>
It has helped demolish four million sq.m of dangerous, run-down
housing to make way for new apartment buildings to move people
into more spacious apartments.
</P>
<P>
More than 30,000 residents of the city's suburban towns and
county seats have left their shabby living quarters and moved into
new apartment buildings with better heating, gas, water and
electricity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
