<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Textile Exports Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's textile exports
increased by 0.5 percent to 67.3 billion baht (2.5 billion U.S.
dollars) in the first half of this year compared with the same
period last year, according to the Thai Garment Manufacturers
Association.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's high-end textiles which were exported under the
quota agreement with the United States, the European Union (EU),
Norway and Canada rose by 1.2 percent to 32.8 billion baht (1.26
billion dollars) in the six-month period when compared to the
corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the volume of low-end textiles which were shipped to
foreign countries with no quota restrictions fell by 4.5 percent
to 34.4 billion baht (1.32 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. represented the strongest growth with a jump of 19.3
percent, worth 18.3 billion baht (703 million dollars) for
Thailand's high-end textiles, followed by Canada with a 8.4
percent increase to 1.1 billion baht (42 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Textile exports to the EU and Norway, however, continued to
decline, with the EU down by 4 percent to 13.2 billion baht (507
million dollars) and Norway down by 1.4 percent to 142 million
baht (5.4 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Suchart Chantaranakracha, the first vice-president of the
association, was quoted by the local press as saying that
Thailand's low-end textiles were still suffering from the loss of
its competitive edge against products from China, particularly in
the Middle East and Central European markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
