<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Teaching Method Experimented For Pupils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 27 (Xinhua) -- An experiment that started 15
years ago on learning to read and write Chinese earlier than usual
now involves 3 million pupils in 30 provinces, regions and
municipalities and about 100,000 teachers.
</P>
<P>
Chinese students used to spend a long time just learning to
read and write because of the characters, which are not based on
an alphabet.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1980s, a group of teachers in Heilongjiang
province began to use a new method, getting the students to learn
characters by reading and writing simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
The students had to write compositions at a younger age and
when they encounter characters they didn't know, had to use the
Chinese Phonetic Alphabet, a system of phonetic symbols.
</P>
<P>
The teachers also employed special textbooks of
transliterations into the Chinese Phonetic Alphabet so that
students could study the texts whether they knew the characters or
not.
</P>
<P>
The new method caught the attention of people elsewhere. Three
new textbooks have been compiled and education departments have
held meetings for teachers to discuss their teaching experience.
</P>
<P>
The experiments showed that reading comprehension and writing
ability increased as a result and that students were more able to
teach themselves and had a wider range of knowledge, and were
better at observation and thinking.
</P>
<P>
The experiment has also attracted interest abroad among
linguists in the United States, Britain, Germany, Japan, and
Australia who think that the new method can help foreigners learn
Chinese.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
