<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Frozen Food Exports Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's frozen food exports
were worth 23.36 billion baht (898 million U.S. dollars) in the
first six months of this year, an increase of 5 percent compared
with the same period last year, according to the figures issued by
the Thai Frozen Foods Association available here today.
</P>
<P>
Exports of frozen shrimp for the period increased by 6.8
percent to 17.95 billion baht (690 million U.S. dollars). frozen
fish exports raised 4.2 percent to 2.05 billion baht (78.8 million
U.S. dollars), while shipments of frozen squid fell by 3.6 percent
to 3.36 billion baht (129 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The united states remained the largest market for Thai frozen
shrimp with value increasing by 4.4 percent to 5.14 billion baht
(197 million U.S. dollars). Japan was second at 5.03 billion baht
(193 million U.S. dollars), a 16.7 percent drop. Next came China
at 1.5 billion baht (57.6 million U.S. dollars), up 6 percent, and
Singapore at 1.12 billion baht (43 million U.S. dollars), down
14.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Japan was the biggest market for Thai frozen squid, at 2.33
billion baht (89.6 million U.S. dollars), down 6.9 percent. Italy
posted 0.5 percent growth to 429.3 million baht (16.5 million U.S.
dollars). next came the united states at 77.3 million baht (2.9
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
For Thai frozen fish, China accounted for 807 million baht (31
million U.S. dollars), down by 6.6 percent. Sales to Japan were
406.7 million baht (15.6 million U.S. dollars), up 51.2 percent,
next came Malaysia at 349.9 million baht (13.4 million U.S.
dollars), up 21.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The values of frozen food exports are expected to increase
sharply in the second half of this year, due mainly to the
depreciation of the baht. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
