<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Classic Arousing More Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 27 (Xinhua) -- Scholars from the fields of
linguistics, archaeology, geography, and history are becoming
interested in the Shan Hai Jing (Classic of Mountains and Seas),
an early Chinese geographical text.
</P>
<P>
The 31,000-character book from the Warring States Period
(403-221 B.C.) was for a long time regarded as a book of folklore
and legends of the geography and peoples of ancient China and
Western regions.
</P>
<P>
Many scholars are now of the opinion that it is an encyclopedia
of ancient times, covering geography, history, minerals, medical
science, religion, meteorology, and astronomy.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese scholars and those from Japan, France, Spain and
elsewhere are interested in the book, according to Professor Gong
Yuhai, chairman of the Shan Hai Jing Society. Yunnan's provincial
science and technology commission established a group in 1994 to
study the book.
</P>
<P>
They have found a close relation between the book and a large
number of petroglyphs dating back to the New Stone Age in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shihao, vice-director of the commission, said that the
study may lead scientists to a better understanding of
civilization's origins.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
