<HEADLINE> Italian FM Defends Decision to Postpone Repatriation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini today denied any link of the government decision to postpone
the repatriation of Albanian refugees with Albania's refusal to
take them back.
</P>
<P>
Dini dismissed reports that Albania had "blackmailed" Italy
into extending the deadline of August 31 for another two months by
threatening not to accept the refugees until Italy delivers its
promised aid.
</P>
<P>
"We aren't blackmailing Albania and they aren't blackmailing
us," Dini told reporters. He said a final decision on returning
the estimated 10,000 refugees in Italy will be made at a cabinet
meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
While rejecting criticism by the opposition that the government
gave in to Albanian pressure, Dini emphasized the fact that "Italy
certainly cannot take the decision to load 10,000 people onto
ships and unload them on Albanian coasts."
</P>
<P>
The government came under mounting fire from the public for
being "too lenient" with Albanian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
About 17,000 Albanians had fled their homeland for neighboring
Italy since spring when the collapse of a shady savings scheme
there sparked nationwide anarchy and plunged the country into a
heavy political and economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Some 7,000 have reportedly returned. Of the remaining 10,000,
it is known that 3,000 remain in Italian refugee camps but the
whereabouts of the others is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
Some of the remaining Albanians would rather stay than go back
home. A refugee spokesman said that returning would mean
"hopelessness" for them who have lost everything in the crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
