<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0310 GMT, August 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine Senate has finally agreed to a 10
percent tax on foreign currency deposits, the Manila Times
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In Tuesday's session, which tackled the last phase of the
Comprehensive Tax Reform Program (CTRP), the Senate voted 12-6 to
approve the 10 percent tax scheme. The Senate is scheduled to
approve the CTRP bill in the next few
days. (Philippines-Tax-Foreign Deposits)
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- London and Dublin have agreed on an international
commission to oversee the hand-over of terrorist weapons during
Northern Ireland peace talks.
</P>
<P>
British Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam and Irish Foreign
Affairs Minister Ray Burke signed an agreement on the commission
during 90 minutes of talks held Tuesday in Belfast. Ministers said
the "Independent International Commission on Decommissioning"
would operate alongside full-scale talks due to start on September
15 and would have offices in Belfast and Dublin. (UK-Ireland-Arms)
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States stores 12,500 nuclear weapons
at 26 locations in 15 states and 150 more in seven foreign
countries, said a report on Tuesday by private nuclear arms
specialists.
</P>
<P>
The report says the total U.S. nuclear stockpile consists of
about 12,500 warheads, of which about 8,750 are fielded with
active "operational" forces. (US-Nuclear-Weapons)
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq urged the U.N. Sanctions Committee to persuade
the United States and Britain to approve the deals that Iraq has
signed with foreign countries under the first stage of the
oil-for-food deal Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the chairman of the sanctions committee, Iraqi
Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed Al-Sahhaf said that despite the
fact that more than two months has elapsed since the end of the
first phase of the deal, more than 60 contracts which were signed
in the first phase, are still frozen, Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He asked the committee to take the necessary measures to
accelerate the implementation of the contracts. (Iraq-U.N.-Deals)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Six Palestinian demonstrators, including a
policeman, were injured as Israeli soldiers fired rubber bullets
and tear gas on Tuesday to disperse protesters in the west Bank
city of Bethlehem during the second day of clashes.
</P>
<P>
The clash took place near the Jewish holy site of Rachel's
Tomb. To protest the ongoing closure imposed by Israel, dozens of
Palestinian youths threw stones at soldiers guarding the site. The
soldiers retaliated with rubber bullets and tear gas.
(Israel-Palestinians-Clash)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Former South African president F. W. De Klerk
announced in Cape Town Tuesday that he will quit politics after 25
years of service.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk, leader of the South African opposition National
Party, told a press conference that "after careful consideration,
I have decided that the time has come for me to retire from active
politics." (Safrica-DE Klerk's Retirement) 
</P>
