</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Li Peng returned to Beijing yesterday after
ending friendly visits to Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
-- The paper praises the Power Administration of Shandong
province for achieving fine economic returns and promoting ethical
and cultural progress.
</P>
<P>
-- The front page carries an interview with Huang Huoqing, one
of the 60 Party veterans to be invited to the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China as a special delegate.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The paper carries a story on China's agricultural
development as well as achievements in its rural economy.
</P>
<P>
-- A Foreign Ministry spokesman announced that Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto will visit China from September 4 to 7
at the invitation of Chinese Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Catholics have expressed the wish to help protect
national unity during a ceremony marking the 40th anniversary of
the Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association held yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- China will intensify its study of more efficient use of
energy in an attempt to achieve sustainable economic development.
</P>
<P>
-- China has pledged to tighten the crackdown on cigarette
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
-- China's switching capacity of the national public telecom
network has exceeded 100 million lines, ranking second in the
world next only to the United States. Program-Control switching
systems have so far been in use in all counties and cities across
the country. 
</P>
