<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Celtic Find Way to UEFA with Dying-minute Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Scottish Celtic sailed into the
lucrative format of the UEFA Cup by sealing a 6-3 victory with
dying-minute goals over Tirol Innsbruck of Austria for 7-5 on
aggregate at Glasgow, Scotland on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Simon Donnelly put Celtic ahead with a 34-minute goal before
the visitors equalized five minutes later by Christian Mayrleb,
double-striker of the first leg.
</P>
<P>
German Andreas Thom drove home from a well-organized free-kick
after 44 minutes and Tirol rallied back anew to level for the
second time through Francis Sebereyns just before the break.
</P>
<P>
In the second-half, Celtic geared up to evaporate Austrians'
hope of the next round at the UEFA.
</P>
<P>
Donnelly scored his second from the penalty spot when onrushing
Swede Henrik Larsson was upended in the area on 68th minute.
Burley scored twice in the 70th and 90th minutes and Wieghorst
joined the spree with his 88-minute goal.
</P>
<P>
Tirol replied with substitute Gurnot Krinner's score in the
82nd minute.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Dundee United went down 2-1 aggregate at Trabzonspor
of Turkey after Hami drew at 1-1 with just nine minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
Andy McLaren kept the United's hope alive when Dave Bowman's
deflected strike was palmed away by the Turkish under-21
international Metin. Lars Zetterlund, unmarked on the left,
collected the rebound from the post before he picked up McLaren
who finished the move.
</P>
<P>
It hushed the crowd before Hami rifled an angled drive with a
solo run to put the Turks firmly in the driving seat.
</P>
<P>
Other highlights saw Hungary's Ferencvaros hammered Sweden's
Helsingborgs 4-3 on penalties after a 1-1 draw on aggregate. The
10-man Malmo slumped into a 2-0 defeat by Croatia's Hajduk Split
with aggregation score of 5-2. First leg hero Jonas Wirmola was
sent off in the first quarter-hour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
