<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil to Invest Heavily in Petrobras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 26 (Xinhua) -- An 18.7 billion
U.S. dollar slice of the capital that flows into the oil and gas
industry of Brazil will be invested in the state-owned oil
company, Petrobras.
</P>
<P>
It will come from the capital inflow into Brazil's oil and gas
industry which will have amounted to 32 billion U.S. dollars by
the year 2002. The estimate comes from a study by Brazil's
Association of Infrastructure and Basic Industries (AIBI).
</P>
<P>
Petrobras will invest 5.12 billion U.S. dollars in 10 projects,
said Jose Augusto Marques, the chairman of AIBI.
</P>
<P>
Such plans must be developed along with private funds, he added.
</P>
<P>
"By the year 2002, private participation in Brazil's oil and
gas industry must reach 6.9 billion dollars", Marques stressed.
</P>
<P>
Among the most important projects for the next four years was a
refinery plant worth 700 million dollars, as well as a
Campos-Victoria pipe line costing 150 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
