<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Open Policy Improves Ties, says Sakurauchi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The president of Japan's
International Trade Promotion Association, Yoshio Sakurauchi, said
here Tuesday that China's reform and open policy has greatly
promoted the development of Sino-Japanese ties in economy and
trade.
</P>
<P>
Sakurauchi, also the former speaker of Japan's Lower House,
said in a written statement delivered to Xinhua that China has
made outstanding achievements in every social field since it
adopted the economic reform and open policy 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The reform and open policy has brought about tremendous
development and changes to Sino-Japanese relations on the economy
and trade, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
According to Sakurauchi, two-way trade amounted to 62.4 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996, compared with 5.1 billion dollars in
1978. China became Japan's second largest trading partner in 1994,
and investment by Japan in China reached 14 billion dollars in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Now, China is not only a big supplier of energy, agricultural
products and semi-manufactured goods, but also a great
manufacturing base and a huge market for Japan, Sakurauchi said.
</P>
<P>
Calling on the two countries to further strengthen bilateral
economic ties, Sakurauchi said: "From the point of view of
strategy, Japan and China should deepen mutual trust and further
enhance close and friendly ties while a new framework is being
established in the world following the collapse of the cold war."
</P>
<P>
Sakurauchi also expressed hope that Japan and China would
further strengthen cooperation and contribute to peace and
stability in Asia and the world at large, into the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Urges Maintaining Single Currency Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Austria urged the European Union
(EU) to observe the timetable set for monetary integration among
all member nations in order to avert economic disaster.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian news agency quoted Wolfgang Schuessel, vice
federal chancellor and foreign minister, as saying that
"preparatory work has already been completed to such an extent
that delaying the launch of the single European currency, the
Euro, could -- like a high-speed train brought to a sudden stop --
result in serious chaos."
</P>
<P>
Schuessel, who made the speech tonight in the Alpbach Forum,
said any postponement would hurt the overall plan for European
integration and lead to confusion in financial and economic
policies. He said any change would bring about distrust among the
world's partners.
</P>
<P>
Austria has already met all the demands of the economic and
monetary union (EMU) except for the state debts, according to
Schuessel.
</P>
<P>
He believes Austria will become a member of the EMU in the
first group.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty, which set the deadline for the issuance
of the Euro on January 1, 1999, has compiled a list of convergence
criteria on budget deficits, debt, inflation, interest rates and
exchange rates that EU member states must meet before they can
join the single currency.
</P>
<P>
But several EU countries are having trouble meeting some of the
criteria, notably the budget deficit conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico to Host World Indoor Soccer Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The sixth World Indoor
Soccer Championships will have the draws on September 22, the
Mexico Indoor Football Association said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The championships, which attracts teams from 20 countries, will
kick off on November 25 and finish on December 6, with the
preliminaries divided into five groups to be spread in Mexico
City, Monterrey, Guadalajara, Puebla and Jalapa.
</P>
<P>
The host Mexico, defending champion Argentina, Slovakia, Spain
and Colombia are seeded teams for the preliminaries, with the
first two teams in each group and the two best third-placers
entering the next round.
</P>
<P>
The last 12 teams will have their round-robins in four groups
in four cities, with the semifinals to be played in two venues
prior to the final and third-place match.
</P>
<P>
The indoor soccer, stemmed from Uruguay in 1930, has become
popular in the American continent since then before the World
Indoor Soccer Association was founded in 1971. 
</P>
</TEXT>
