<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Strengthen Role in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will dispatch
more staff to its resident mission in China and seek an enhanced
role in that rapidly growing country, a senior World Bank official
said.
</P>
<P>
The staff assigned by the Washington-based headquarters will
increase to 16 from the present level of 6-7 in two years, while
more local competent people will be hired, Yukon Huang, director
of the China Program and chief of the Resident Mission in China,
told Xinhua here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Huang, an American national educated at Yale University, was
assigned to this new post in July after serving the World Bank for
over 20 years, including three years as director of the Country
Department III. He plans to leave for Beijing in late October.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is empowered to make 80 percent of the relevant
decisions, a privilege his predecessors did not enjoy. The change
came within the framework of the "Strategic Compact" introduced in
the world financial institution last year to improve its
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will continue to provide assistance to China's
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"Ninety percent of these projects are performing well," said
Huang, who also said that "they (the Chinese) are more careful and
more focused on doing some things."
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank will pay more attention to the central
and interior parts of China, which are not as economically
developed as the coastal regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
