<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss-U.S. Bank to Sell Costa Rican Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- A Swiss-United States joint
venture bank has won the bid to sell bonds for the Costa Rican
government on the international market.
</P>
<P>
The Banco Credit Suisses First Boston will launch an auction
overseas for 200 million U.S. dollars worth of Costa Rican bonds,
Costa Rican finance officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican government will use the money to replace part
of its domestic debt as the international interest rates are lower
than the home levels.
</P>
<P>
The bank will get a commission of one million dollars for
auctioning the bonds, which several other big financial firms, JP
Morgan, Salomon Brothers and Deustsche Morgan Grenfell, had also
been competing for.
</P>
<P>
Vice Finance Minister Marvin Taylor said one of the reasons the
bank was chosen was that it was an European-U.S. bank, and Costa
Rica looked forward to having a solid participation in the United
States market.
</P>
<P>
The bank said it would support the secondary market to assure
the stability of the bonds' price. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate OKs 10 Pct Tax on Foreign Deposits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate has finally
agreed to a 10 percent tax on foreign currency deposits, the
Manila Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
In Tuesday's session which tackled the last phase of the
Comprehensive Tax Reform Program (CTRP), the Senate voted 12-6 to
approve the 10 percent tax scheme, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Senator Juan Ponce Enrile, chairman of the Senate Ways and
Means Committee, had earlier proposed a 20 percent tax on foreign
currency deposits to align it with the prevailing rate on peso
deposits.
</P>
<P>
At present, foreign currency deposits are not subject to any
tax in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mainly because of the government's lax tax treatment, foreign
currency deposits grew from virtually nothing in the early 1980s
to the current 14 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bankers are worried that the imposition of the tax may trigger
a capital flight while others opposing the scheme believe that the
tax may act as a deterrent to foreign investors whose investments
have helped spur the growth of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is scheduled to approve the CTRP bill in the next
few days. The bill will then go through the bicameral conference
committee to allow representatives of the upper and lower chambers
to reconcile their conflicts, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fredericks Completes Four Wins in Golden Four </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Namibian sprinter Frankie
Fredericks completed his mission of four wins in a row by winning
the last stop of the Golden Four athletics series in Berlin,
Germany on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian clokced 9.99 seconds in the 100 meters, beating
world champion Canadian Donovan Bailey to second.
</P>
<P>
Thus, Fredericks became the first athlete to complete the four
triumphs in the sprint after taking titles in Oslo, Zurich and
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Fredericks dashed ahead with a strong finish, edging Canadian
Bailey and American Tim Montgomery to second sharing in 10.05.
</P>
<P>
Fredericks will share the prize with Romanian Gabriela Szabo,
who claimed her fourth victory in the women's 5,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
In the Golden Four series, a jackpot of 20 one-kilo-gold bars
is awarded to athletes who win specific events at all the four
meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
