<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Prime Minister John Howard unleashed an
extraordinary attack on state premiers yesterday, vowing to
respond with gusto to what he described as their unfair attacks on
the Federal government.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Sweden has been rocked by reports that 60,000 people, mainly
women, were forcibly sterilized between 1935 and 1976 under a
"racial hygiene" program organized by the now defunct Institute
for Racial Biology.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Japan wants to scrap its two-yearly ministerial meetings
with Australia, widely regarded in Canberra as the centerpiece of
bilateral relations, on the ground that they have become unwieldy
and time-wasting.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Australian banks have been beaten by the country's
communications giant Telstra in the race to be first into the
crucial smart card market and now face being sidelined in the
battle to cement customer relationships.
</P>
<P>
The Telstra smart cards, which use electronic chips to store
relatively large amounts of information, can provide a wide range
of services on a single card, such as bill payment, ticketing,
records storage, tracking loyalty programs and customizing mobile
phones.  
</P>
</TEXT>
