<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Financing for Armenia, Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today approved
a total of 295 million U.S. dollars in financing for projects in
Armenia and Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The financing includes 60 million dollars for Armenia's second
Structural Adjustment Credit (SAC II) and 5 million dollars for
the country's second Structural Adjustment Technical Assistant
Credit (SATAC II).
</P>
<P>
The SAC II will support the Armenian government's program to
consolidate macro-economic stability and to lay the foundations
for sustained private-sector led growth. The SATAC II will be used
to finance technical assistance in support of the government's
economic reform programs.
</P>
<P>
The credits will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary
lending arm for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The financing also includes a 230 million dollar loan for
Kazakhstan public sector resource management adjustment project.
</P>
<P>
The project will support the government's institutional and
policy reform program, which is designed to increase budget
revenues through improved resources mobilization and better target
government spending through a more efficient use of the limited
resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
