<HEADLINE> Mowlam Announces Panel on IRA Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- London and Dublin have agreed on
an international commission to oversee the hand-over of terrorist
weapons during Northern Ireland peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Ministers said the "Independent International Commission on
Decommissioning" would operate alongside full-scale talks due to
start on September 15 and would have offices in Belfast and
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
British Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam and Irish Foreign
Affairs Minister Ray Burke signed an agreement on the commission
during 90 minutes of talks in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Ireland hope that the establishment of a commission
to supervise a handover of armaments will be a spur for
multi-party talks that have been paralyzed by rows over the
illegal weaponry for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody knows that we cannot force people to hand in
weapons," Mowlam said. "But what we have is a structure to
facilitate that from day one of talks," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
