<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan the Big Winner in Universiade Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CATANIA, Sicily, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Japan was the biggest winner
on the opening day of the Universiade swimming tournament by taking
three out of six golds on offer here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The American swimmers won two titles while the remaining gold was
taken by Hungarian.
</P>
<P>
The athletics tournament of the Universiade also began on Tuesday.
The four gold medals of the day were split by Hungary, the United
States, Belarus and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The United States won the first gold of the swimming tournament
through Suzanne L. Black who clocked 8:45.82 for the women's 800
meters freestyle title.
</P>
<P>
But it was the Japanese swimmers who enjoyed the greatest success
in the pool.
</P>
<P>
Junko Onishi gave Japan the first swimming gold as she beat all her
opponents to take the women's 100 meters butterfly title with a time
of 1:00.40.
</P>
<P>
Fumie Kurotori followed suite with a victory in the women's 400
meters individual medley. Her winning time was 4:46.20.
</P>
<P>
Japan's third swimming gold of the day came from Chikara Nakashita
who snatched the title of the men's 200 meters breaststroke with a
time of 2:16.35.
</P>
<P>
The last swimming event of the day, the women's 4X200 meters
freestyle relay, was won by the American quartet.
</P>
<P>
The race was also the most one-sided contest of the day as the
Americans enjoyed a great advantage in the race and beat the eventual
runners-up Australia by more than 14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The Americans' winning time was 8:12.16, the Australia came second
at 8:26.97 and the Italians finished third at 8;27.11.
</P>
<P>
The men's 200 meters freestyle gold was taken by Bela Szabados of
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The four finals of athletics on Tuesday was men's 20km walk,
women's 10km walk, men's hammer and women's 5,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Olympic silver medalist Ilia Markov of Russia won the men's 20km
walk with a time of one hour 25 minutes and 36 seconds, followed by
Alejandro Lopez of Mexico in the second place at 1:26:00. Arturo Di
Mezza of Italy came third in 1:26:12.
</P>
<P>
The women's 10km walk was won by Larissa Ramazanova of Belarus who
was timed at 44 minutes and one second.
</P>
<P>
Rossella Giordano of Italy finished second at 44:31, followed by
her compatriot Annarita Sidoti in the third place at 44:38. Sidoti is
the reigning world champion of the event.
</P>
<P>
Balage Kiss of Hungary, gold medalist at 1996 Atlanta Olympic
Games, won his specialty of hammer with a throw of 79.42 meters.
</P>
<P>
The last athletics gold of the day went to Nnenna Lynch of the
United States who clocked 15 minutes and 47.61 seconds in the women's
5,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine won their third fencing gold medals at the Universiade in
the men's foil team event. The Ukrainian team beat Cuba 45-37 in the
final.
</P>
<P>
China got the bronze medal after beating hosts Italy 45-42 in the
third place playoff.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei won its their first gold at the games in the women's
tennis doubles final. South Korean combination won the men's doubles
title.
</P>
<P>
The soccer semi-finals were decided by penalty kicks on Tuesday.
Hosts Italy were awarded a penalty at the 64th minute and made no
mistakes in converting it to beat the United States 1-0.
</P>
<P>
The other semi-final match between South Korea and ended in a
goalless draw. In the penalty shoot-out, the South Koreans missed
none of their first five kicks while the Ukrainians missed two. The
South Koreans went through to the final slated for August 31.
</P>
<P>
The second diving event, the men's one-meter springboard, was taken
by unknown Hungarian Inre Lengyel. Lengyel finsihed second in the
preliminary but surged ahead in the semi-finals and again beat his
Chinese opponent Wang Tianling in the final.
</P>
<P>
Wang, national champion of China, had to be satisfied with a
silver. Chris Lepoole of Canada won the bronze medal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
