<HEADLINE> U.S. Air Force Faces Pilot Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Air Force expects to
have 350 fewer pilots than it needs next fiscal year and to suffer
pilot shortages for all aircraft types the year after, an
Associated Press report said today.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted Brig. Gen. John F. Regni, the director
of military personnel policy for the service, as saying that at
present, the Air Force is short fighter pilots and those who fly
C-130 warplanes.
</P>
<P>
By fiscal year 1999, "all our weapons systems... will be
undermanned," includes pilots for tankers, transports and fighter
planes, he said.
</P>
<P>
Regni attributed the shortage to the lure of high pay among
commercial airlines, the end of the challenge of the Cold War, and
cutbacks in personnel that translate to increased probability
pilots will be sent overseas on lengthier deployments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
