<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: U.S. Stores 12,500 Nuclear Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States stores
12,500 nuclear weapons at 26 locations in 15 states and 150 more
in seven foreign countries, said a report by private nuclear arms
specialists.
</P>
<P>
Details about locations of nuclear weapons is an official
government secret, but Robert Norris and William Arkin said they
did their own accounting from public records, including
information associated with security at nuclear storage sites.
</P>
<P>
Norris and Arkin compiled the information for a coming report,
to be published by the private Natural Resources Defense Council,
on the location of nuclear weapons not only in America but also in
other countries.
</P>
<P>
The report says the total U.S. nuclear stockpile consists of
about 12,500 warheads, of which about 8,750 are fielded with
active "operational" forces. The rest either are held as a
"hedge," meaning they could be returned to active status; are
emergency backups in the event of safety problems, or are retired
and awaiting dismantlement at the Pantex plant in Texas.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear stockpile stood at about 24,000 weapons in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, nuclear weapons have been withdrawn from 10 states.
At present, New Mexico and Georgia are two states hold the largest
number of nuclear weapons. New Mexico holds about 2,850 nuclear
weapons and 2,000 in Georgia, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The King's Bay naval base in Georgia is home to 10 Trident
nuclear submarines armed with Trident I and the more advanced
Trident II nuclear missiles.
</P>
<P>
Washington state ranks third with a total of 1,600 nuclear
warheads. It holds eight Trident submarines at Bangor.
Approximately half the weapons assigned to Bangor and King's Bay
are aboard subs at sea at any given time, according to the
specialists.
</P>
<P>
The report listed other states with numbers of nuclear weapons.
They are Nevada with 1,450, including Air Force cruise missiles
and bombs in storage at Nellis Air Force Base, and North Dakota
with 965, including intercontinental ballistic missiles at Grand
Forks and Minot Air Force bases.
</P>
<P>
Also, Wyoming has 592 warheads, Missouri 550, Texas 520,
Louisiana 455, Montanactical nuclear bombs in
Europe, report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970827.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Adjustments in Four Argentine Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today approved
four adjustment loans totaling 300 million U.S. dollars to back
fiscal and public financing reforms in four Argentine provinces
---Rio Negro, Salta, San Juan and Tucuman.
</P>
<P>
In Argentina, the public sector is highly decentralized. The
country's 24 provincial governments are responsible for 45 percent
of Argentina's public expenditures, and in 1995 they undertook 97
percent of public basic education costs, 92 percent of public
health outlays, and 84 percent of public welfare expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The four loans are designed to help reform and restructure
their governments to ensure efficient and responsive delivery of
public services, specially social services to the poor, while
improving fiscal accounts.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will also provide technical assistance and
analytical support for the four provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
